1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:29,040
 I can do a little pre-see on what my investment, like why I was reading this to begin with.

2
00:00:29,040 --> 00:00:35,620
 I mean, in terms of the like subtitle of my book, I'm thinking of style in terms of thinking, thinking slash writing.

3
00:00:35,740 --> 00:00:44,020
 And that's what I'm calling it right now is thinking writing, because I kind of don't want to choose the material instantiation or the sort of mental thing.

4
00:00:44,380 --> 00:00:48,380
 When I'm talking about style in my book, I'm not in the style of thinking.

5
00:00:48,480 --> 00:00:51,480
 Right. That's a phrase that I use a lot.

6
00:00:52,040 --> 00:01:01,140
 And but I am what I'm not concerned with there is the mental process that went in in the mind of Deleuze or the mental process in the mind of Derrida.

7
00:01:01,560 --> 00:01:05,340
 Or I'm not. When I say style of thinking, I'm not. I don't mean that.

8
00:01:05,520 --> 00:01:08,220
 I mean the style of thinking in the writing. Right.

9
00:01:08,260 --> 00:01:14,820
 Like it is thinking slash writing. And actually, Heidegger does give me ways of saying, here's one of the things that thinking is not.

10
00:01:14,940 --> 00:01:21,500
 It's not just a mental operation that occurs in your head that secondarily gets instantiated in language.

11
00:01:21,500 --> 00:01:25,860
 Right. Because for him, there's no thinking without language. Right.

12
00:01:25,940 --> 00:01:32,800
 The thinking or the way that I like to take it is thinking only operates in relation with some practice.

13
00:01:32,800 --> 00:01:35,660
 It doesn't. There is no such thing as just thinking.

14
00:01:35,860 --> 00:01:40,360
 There is thinking in language, thinking in writing, thinking in sound, thinking in images.

15
00:01:40,620 --> 00:01:46,480
 You know, like I'm fine. It doesn't really matter what the sort of so-called incarnation is.

16
00:01:46,540 --> 00:01:49,820
 But it's not that there's thinking first and then you. Right.

17
00:01:49,880 --> 00:01:54,800
 There is you could you could think in your head in words and then you could write it down.

18
00:01:54,800 --> 00:02:04,500
 That's possible, too. But there's no prior thinking that happens first and then, you know, writing or something else comes afterwards.

19
00:02:04,800 --> 00:02:06,200
 That's that's what I'm trying to do.

20
00:02:06,600 --> 00:02:10,180
 But I mean, in the first lecture, you know, I mean, this is the quote that you're after.

21
00:02:10,500 --> 00:02:13,120
 And only when man speaks does he think. Right.

22
00:02:13,200 --> 00:02:16,060
 Not the other way around, as metaphysics still believes.

23
00:02:16,060 --> 00:02:20,520
 Right. Right. I mean, that's, you know, so that's the key starting point.

24
00:02:20,600 --> 00:02:21,780
 He gets he gives me that.

25
00:02:22,560 --> 00:02:31,920
 And like I said, I want a broader scope because it doesn't have to be like let's we have to then understand language very broad or speaking very broadly there as well.

26
00:02:31,920 --> 00:02:42,840
 Because to me, there's no reason that we're not talking about images or music or anything else like thinking doesn't have a necessary purchase on, you know, sort of verbal language necessarily.

27
00:02:42,840 --> 00:02:46,060
 Right. Like but but what it does have is a relational.

28
00:02:46,340 --> 00:02:49,840
 It has a fundamentally related. There's no such thing as thinking itself.

29
00:02:50,200 --> 00:02:58,620
 There is only thinking with to plug the podcast and and everything is relational to the wood is relational.

30
00:02:58,620 --> 00:03:04,900
 Right. I mean, there's no thing in itself, an object for Heidegger, it would seem in these first three lectures, at least.

31
00:03:04,900 --> 00:03:14,120
 Right. I mean, it's like the the essence of wood is its relation to either a person or to some its malleability is its essence, basically.

32
00:03:14,120 --> 00:03:29,380
 You know, so like it is that sense of essence that I I was really drawn to thinking here as well, because it is such a relational notion of essence, which is precisely, you know, 180 degrees opposite of what you would think of the essence.

33
00:03:29,540 --> 00:03:32,340
 You know, the essence is the thing that it is in and of itself.

34
00:03:32,340 --> 00:03:46,020
 But here, I mean, because of the, you know, the very Heideggerian move to think about, you know, any set of relations, any approach, any perspective to something is going to allow a certain disclosure and a certain withdrawal.

35
00:03:46,020 --> 00:03:49,080
 Like, at the same time, force this force a certain kind of withdrawal.

36
00:03:49,260 --> 00:03:56,700
 And so when he's talking about essence up front, you know, part of me, you know, withdrew at that.

37
00:03:56,700 --> 00:04:05,440
 But I just but, you know, also kind of new in Heideggerian fashion, you know, what counts as essence is going to get undone a bit.

38
00:04:05,840 --> 00:04:19,460
 Yeah, that speaks to every single time I encounter Heidegger, I have this same kind of reaction, which is a very negative one to what I consider his sort of bucolic and naturalist sensibilities.

39
00:04:20,920 --> 00:04:25,920
 But I have read enough that I know that as you go through it, it's not going to stay there.

40
00:04:26,100 --> 00:04:38,880
 And it speaks to what you just said, because when I was reading the essence stuff, I had the same reaction, which was like, oh, Jesus, the essence of the hand is like, I mean, when I hear that, I just everything about me just goes, oh, God.

41
00:04:39,540 --> 00:04:45,880
 But but I have enough confidence that it's not going to end up being something that's located in the hand, you know.

42
00:04:46,540 --> 00:04:47,020
 Right.

43
00:04:47,480 --> 00:04:57,000
 So but but it's nevertheless, the fact that I know that, like, obviously, he and he is very much a thinker of movement, the paths of thought.

44
00:04:57,000 --> 00:05:00,300
 Right. It's, you know, and the non propositional dimension.

45
00:05:00,940 --> 00:05:08,700
 And yet the particular style that is characteristic of Heidegger is one that always grates on me.

46
00:05:09,020 --> 00:05:09,340
 Always.

47
00:05:10,360 --> 00:05:12,740
 Yeah, it's a little self-indulgent.

48
00:05:12,900 --> 00:05:14,180
 He has an authoritative tone.

49
00:05:14,300 --> 00:05:16,920
 Yeah, it's a bit self-indulgent in terms of the etymology.

50
00:05:17,100 --> 00:05:28,300
 You know, he almost it feels arbitrarily authoritative, you know, when he pulls out, you know, the the etymology of something like, you know, pick a word, whatever it is.

51
00:05:28,400 --> 00:05:32,580
 And this essentially means and then it is this.

52
00:05:32,940 --> 00:05:35,080
 But then there's always such an interesting read.

53
00:05:35,340 --> 00:05:35,560
 Right.

54
00:05:35,620 --> 00:05:36,440
 Of that word.

55
00:05:36,440 --> 00:05:40,120
 And then, you know, that authoritarianism, I always find.

56
00:05:40,280 --> 00:05:43,540
 I always think, like, you couldn't get away with this type of writing.

57
00:05:44,040 --> 00:05:49,620
 Well, really, at any era, but particularly today, I mean, imagine trying to write in that fashion.

58
00:05:49,900 --> 00:05:51,440
 Again, I find it interesting at times.

59
00:05:51,440 --> 00:06:03,220
 But like he always deconstructs his own grammar and sentences and then kind of tells you, like, why it's important that he says that we have still not or we're still not thinking.

60
00:06:03,380 --> 00:06:03,540
 Right.

61
00:06:03,540 --> 00:06:07,780
 He'll like isolate little parts of his thesis and say, this is why this is.

62
00:06:08,040 --> 00:06:14,000
 And it's like, I mean, it is interesting, but it's also very just like masturbatory in a way.

63
00:06:14,100 --> 00:06:15,020
 Like he's just constantly.

64
00:06:15,100 --> 00:06:16,020
 You wrote that sentence, Marty.

65
00:06:16,500 --> 00:06:22,640
 And why do we use phrases such as and it's like, well, you used it, man.

66
00:06:22,720 --> 00:06:25,460
 I mean, it's not like it's not like it's a quote from Aristotle.

67
00:06:25,460 --> 00:06:25,920
 Right.

68
00:06:25,940 --> 00:06:30,120
 Like it's what is most thought provoking about our era is that we are not yet thinking.

69
00:06:30,320 --> 00:06:31,780
 And it's like you said that.

70
00:06:32,060 --> 00:06:34,000
 What do we do with what do we do with this statement?

71
00:06:34,100 --> 00:06:34,960
 How do we understand it?

72
00:06:34,960 --> 00:06:37,000
 It's like you just asserted it.

73
00:06:39,000 --> 00:06:42,720
 It is incredibly professorial in that regard.

74
00:06:42,720 --> 00:06:47,560
 I actually think that is so central to what is going on here.

75
00:06:47,720 --> 00:06:53,400
 And I mean, this is why I said that authority sort of stretches past his breaking point when he does it.

76
00:06:54,300 --> 00:07:05,040
 Just because there is a kind of an opening up or a subjection to a difference, even if that difference seems to have been, you know, auto generated.

77
00:07:05,040 --> 00:07:06,220
 It's like here's a sentence.

78
00:07:06,660 --> 00:07:06,960
 Right.

79
00:07:07,320 --> 00:07:19,520
 Now I'm going to get carried away by that sentence that, you know, isn't simply the instantiation of something that I've already thought and set forth and that I have some kind of mastery over.

80
00:07:19,600 --> 00:07:24,320
 Despite the fact that it's issue for for me, it is not simply mine.

81
00:07:24,320 --> 00:07:35,680
 And then actually attending to the directions and relationships in it is going to propel me in different ways that I can't foresee.

82
00:07:36,260 --> 00:07:36,840
 Right, right.

83
00:07:36,960 --> 00:07:37,760
 But yeah, we're sitting.

84
00:07:38,060 --> 00:07:38,300
 Yeah.

85
00:07:38,560 --> 00:07:40,480
 And I get that.

86
00:07:40,540 --> 00:07:41,920
 But man, it doesn't feel that way.

87
00:07:41,980 --> 00:07:43,740
 Like it feels when I'm reading it.

88
00:07:43,880 --> 00:07:51,620
 It really does feel like every pearl that drops from my mouth is worthy of even my own scrutiny.

89
00:07:52,120 --> 00:07:53,820
 Right, right, right, right.

90
00:07:54,280 --> 00:07:55,540
 I'm going to quote myself.

91
00:07:55,860 --> 00:07:56,600
 God, right.

92
00:07:56,740 --> 00:07:56,860
 Yeah.

93
00:07:56,960 --> 00:07:59,420
 I'm quoting myself when I say the Eric Stoltz line, right?

94
00:08:01,040 --> 00:08:01,440
 Yeah.

95
00:08:01,520 --> 00:08:09,420
 I mean, a lot of it feels experimental, like explicitly he's trying to be experimental or just poetic, right?

96
00:08:09,420 --> 00:08:17,880
 I mean, because he's clearly invested in poetry and the repetition of the central question or thesis about have we begun thinking we're not.

97
00:08:18,020 --> 00:08:23,480
 I mean, it's just word for word every time, and I get that it's a lecture, so maybe that's part of the function of it.

98
00:08:23,480 --> 00:08:29,040
 But it also seems like that's a stylistic choice, you know, for publication maybe as well.

99
00:08:29,040 --> 00:08:34,000
 Like, I want to repeat the same exact clause again and again, which is so –

100
00:08:34,000 --> 00:08:35,040
 It's different every time.

101
00:08:35,280 --> 00:08:35,800
 Oh, is it?

102
00:08:36,080 --> 00:08:36,340
 Okay.

103
00:08:36,700 --> 00:08:37,080
 No, no, no.

104
00:08:37,340 --> 00:08:38,240
 Oh, yes.

105
00:08:38,600 --> 00:08:49,100
 But every time it repeats, it's at a different moment in this pathway and sort of, you know, different parts of it are withdrawn and disclosed.

106
00:08:49,280 --> 00:08:56,580
 Right, but it's just – it is very foreign to at least modern or, you know, contemporary academic writing, right?

107
00:08:56,580 --> 00:09:03,700
 Because you have a thesis and then you have to build on it and then change it in some way at the end of the piece or throughout the piece.

108
00:09:03,780 --> 00:09:06,440
 So it's like you can't just simply repeat yourself.

109
00:09:06,640 --> 00:09:08,200
 But Heidegger's like, well, I'm going to do that.

110
00:09:09,820 --> 00:09:23,820
 He also implicitly often – and I know that this doesn't hold up, but he often seems to have this like progressive version of philosophy, which is like these people who came later couldn't figure it out, but I figured it out.

111
00:09:23,980 --> 00:09:32,780
 Like he does always – and like the Nietzsche books are paradigmatic in this, like seeing Nietzsche as the last metaphysician because he couldn't quite get out of metaphysics.

112
00:09:33,460 --> 00:09:38,300
 And that's positioning himself as sort of beyond Nietzsche because he recognizes something that Nietzsche didn't.

113
00:09:38,480 --> 00:09:42,780
 And there's that – I mean I often read that and I read that here, right?

114
00:09:42,840 --> 00:09:49,400
 This sort of sense of a progression of thinking that's implicit in terms of how he understands.

115
00:09:49,560 --> 00:09:56,200
 And I know that it's not – there are really easy ways of problematizing that as we go through this.

116
00:09:56,280 --> 00:09:56,740
 There will be.

117
00:09:56,840 --> 00:10:00,140
 But it still feels that way.

118
00:10:00,300 --> 00:10:03,000
 So it just – I've never clicked with how to go.

119
00:10:03,000 --> 00:10:03,420
 Well, there's ego.

120
00:10:03,920 --> 00:10:05,140
 There's definitely ego there.

121
00:10:05,180 --> 00:10:07,380
 But there's ego in that whole German tradition.

122
00:10:07,380 --> 00:10:09,960
 I mean they all thought they were the best, right?

123
00:10:10,040 --> 00:10:15,440
 I mean even when they were talking with each other, Kant, with Hegel, with Schelling, they were all like, fuck you.

124
00:10:15,800 --> 00:10:16,840
 I got the answers.

125
00:10:17,000 --> 00:10:17,520
 You don't.

126
00:10:17,980 --> 00:10:19,240
 Heidegger's way after all them.

127
00:10:19,320 --> 00:10:22,800
 But he'll just dismiss Kant and Hegel like with a sentence here and there.

128
00:10:23,100 --> 00:10:24,160
 Like they were great.

129
00:10:24,620 --> 00:10:25,420
 Don't get me wrong.

130
00:10:25,500 --> 00:10:26,080
 They were great.

131
00:10:26,160 --> 00:10:34,080
 But they totally missed all – the entire part about technology that's actually the fulcrum of a modern philosophy, you know, or whatever.

132
00:10:34,380 --> 00:10:39,600
 He's like – it's because it would have been impossible for them given where they were.

133
00:10:39,600 --> 00:10:39,780
 That's true.

134
00:10:40,120 --> 00:10:40,260
 Yeah.

135
00:10:40,480 --> 00:10:43,660
 Like they pushed it as far as they could given where they were at.

136
00:10:43,660 --> 00:10:44,000
 Right, right.

137
00:10:44,000 --> 00:10:44,540
 They tried.

138
00:10:44,640 --> 00:10:45,300
 Things had to develop.

139
00:10:45,800 --> 00:10:47,540
 But that's – what do you mean to his credit?

140
00:10:47,640 --> 00:10:49,460
 That's like ultra-condescending.

141
00:10:49,780 --> 00:10:50,620
 Yeah, yeah, yeah.

142
00:10:51,000 --> 00:10:55,060
 It's not really Hegel's – it's not really Hegel's fault that he wasn't as smart as I am.

143
00:10:55,120 --> 00:10:56,760
 He was stuck in the 1970s.

144
00:11:07,660 --> 00:11:13,260
 The stuff about teaching I felt was like very resonant with your approach, John.

145
00:11:13,340 --> 00:11:16,580
 Like the stuff – it's sort of a dispositional pedagogy, right?

146
00:11:16,580 --> 00:11:28,200
 Like teach people how to learn and how to think and – like it's basically cultivating a way of cultivating is basically his pedagogy.

147
00:11:28,360 --> 00:11:32,780
 And it's like I've heard you say some version of that several times.

148
00:11:32,900 --> 00:11:38,000
 And I think that's – it's so relevant to contemporary pedagogies.

149
00:11:38,860 --> 00:11:39,780
 So here's that line.

150
00:11:40,080 --> 00:11:41,880
 It's on page 15 in the first lecture.

151
00:11:42,060 --> 00:11:42,220
 Yeah.

152
00:11:42,820 --> 00:11:44,920
 Teaching is even more difficult than learning.

153
00:11:45,120 --> 00:11:45,840
 We know that.

154
00:11:45,900 --> 00:11:47,260
 But we rarely think about it.

155
00:11:47,440 --> 00:11:49,300
 And why is teaching more difficult than learning?

156
00:11:49,700 --> 00:11:54,520
 Not because the teacher must have a larger store of information and have it always at the ready.

157
00:11:55,200 --> 00:12:00,960
 Teaching is more difficult than learning because what teaching calls for is this, to let learn.

158
00:12:00,960 --> 00:12:05,420
 The real teacher, in fact, lets nothing else be learned than learning.

159
00:12:05,880 --> 00:12:21,480
 And there is – this is – I'm going to focus on this I think a lot or this is I think probably going to be the fulcrum of my approach to this entire book is that allowing to let – like creating the conditions of possibility for something else to arise.

160
00:12:21,480 --> 00:12:29,700
 And the – it's not an active move but it's also not as simply a passive move either.

161
00:12:30,060 --> 00:12:41,240
 And that the negotiation, the allowing of oneself to be possessed but not passive is at the heart of a lot of what's going on here.

162
00:12:41,300 --> 00:12:46,640
 And it's only that that allows me to temper a lot of what sounds like is arrogance and authority.

163
00:12:47,040 --> 00:12:50,300
 You know, he's like the activity of letting learn.

164
00:12:50,580 --> 00:12:50,940
 Right.

165
00:12:51,120 --> 00:12:56,160
 Well, first of all, there's at least a very brief critique of like content-based pedagogies.

166
00:12:56,380 --> 00:13:05,840
 So like what teaching is not is what you would traditionally call teaching, which is like biology or whatever where you learn stuff and then apply it to something or you learn a system.

167
00:13:05,840 --> 00:13:10,500
 I mean Heidegger's method of teaching and learning is much more diffuse and ambiguous.

168
00:13:11,380 --> 00:13:12,600
 I mean, right, it's learning –

169
00:13:12,600 --> 00:13:14,100
 My analogy could be taught that way.

170
00:13:14,100 --> 00:13:14,740
 Sure, sure.

171
00:13:14,820 --> 00:13:15,400
 It just tends not to be.

172
00:13:15,520 --> 00:13:15,860
 Right.

173
00:13:15,860 --> 00:13:19,260
 Neither does, you know, anything in the humanities either.

174
00:13:19,500 --> 00:13:20,320
 Exactly, right.

175
00:13:20,380 --> 00:13:25,800
 But how would we characterize his – what does learning mean for Heidegger then?

176
00:13:26,240 --> 00:13:29,120
 Because teaching means teaching people how to learn.

177
00:13:29,540 --> 00:13:32,340
 But what is learning, you know?

178
00:13:32,900 --> 00:13:45,300
 Well, this is where he's got that tight network of relationships because, you know, if you want to think about thinking, then you have to go right to learning and then learning goes right to teaching and then you kind of get bounced in between those three terms.

179
00:13:45,560 --> 00:13:46,380
 Well, we know –

180
00:13:46,380 --> 00:13:47,840
 I mean I think that's worth hashing out.

181
00:13:47,920 --> 00:13:57,720
 We know one thing that learning is not, and you just mentioned it, but he says his conduct, therefore, often produces the impression that we properly learn nothing from him.

182
00:13:57,800 --> 00:13:59,040
 This is the real teacher.

183
00:13:59,540 --> 00:14:03,780
 If by learning we now suddenly understand merely the procurement of useful information.

184
00:14:04,220 --> 00:14:10,480
 So that's one thing that for him learning is not is the procurement of useful information, which, by the way, is content delivery.

185
00:14:10,480 --> 00:14:18,120
 Like that is 99% of what people understand by teaching these days and learning is I want to acquire useful information.

186
00:14:18,120 --> 00:14:24,400
 And he's at the get-go, you know, on early pages saying that's not learning, you know.

187
00:14:24,800 --> 00:14:31,320
 So here's one on learning, and he says it several times almost verbatim or even verbatim.

188
00:14:31,420 --> 00:14:33,240
 So this is on eight in the first lecture.

189
00:14:33,680 --> 00:14:42,060
 To learn means to make everything we do answer to whatever essentials address themselves to us at a given moment.

190
00:14:42,500 --> 00:14:51,000
 And that was difficult for me to wrap my head around the first couple of times until we brought up the example of the woodworking.

191
00:14:51,320 --> 00:14:53,880
 And, you know, like in the margins, I had written involvement.

192
00:14:54,040 --> 00:14:57,560
 I was kind of waiting for him to talk about a kind of involvement, and then he dies.

193
00:14:57,560 --> 00:15:14,080
 But learning is an involvement where one becomes caught up, wholly caught up in the disclosure of something else.

194
00:15:14,460 --> 00:15:16,940
 And so what does it mean to learn woodworking?

195
00:15:17,240 --> 00:15:21,840
 Well, I mean, he's quite explicit, you know, about it not being content delivery.

196
00:15:21,840 --> 00:15:23,620
 It's not learning to use the tools.

197
00:15:23,800 --> 00:15:27,940
 It's not learning tips and tricks and pieces of knowledge.

198
00:15:28,140 --> 00:15:44,600
 It is that involvement with the woodness of the wood and, you know, being able to see the, you know, the lines or the forms that the wood allows to be possible.

199
00:15:44,600 --> 00:15:55,500
 See, that's where it gets tricky because it actually – and, I mean, this is the problem with the hierarchization because it's like he doesn't – he's just not pluralist enough.

200
00:15:55,720 --> 00:16:03,000
 Like he really does believe there's real learning in teaching and there's bullshit learning in teaching, right?

201
00:16:03,340 --> 00:16:07,040
 This is where the authenticity conversation is coming up and I can repeat over and over again.

202
00:16:07,040 --> 00:16:22,800
 I know, I know, and I hate that, and I know – I mean, I don't want to be saying that endlessly, but that's how I feel with the woodworking example is like there's one level on which, you know, if we go to the woodworking thing, it's the true cabinet maker.

203
00:16:22,800 --> 00:16:26,020
 This is like just before the stuff that we read on 14, right?

204
00:16:27,780 --> 00:16:31,680
 A cabinet maker's apprentice, someone who is learning to build cabinets, will serve as an example.

205
00:16:32,140 --> 00:16:40,340
 His learning is not mere practice to gain facility in the use of tools, nor does he merely gather knowledge about the customary forms of things he is to build.

206
00:16:40,780 --> 00:16:48,340
 If he is to become a true cabinet maker, he makes himself answer and respond above all to the different kinds of wood and to the shapes slumbering within the wood.

207
00:16:48,340 --> 00:16:51,340
 It's especially that second phrase that –

208
00:16:51,340 --> 00:16:55,320
 To wood is it enters into man's dwelling with all the hidden riches of its nature.

209
00:16:55,480 --> 00:16:58,800
 In fact, its relatedness to wood is what maintains the whole craft.

210
00:16:59,180 --> 00:17:03,040
 Without the relatedness, the craft will never be anything but empty, busy work.

211
00:17:03,180 --> 00:17:07,680
 Any occupation with it will be determined exclusively by business concerns.

212
00:17:08,240 --> 00:17:12,620
 Every handicraft – all human dealings are constantly in that danger.

213
00:17:12,700 --> 00:17:15,160
 The writing of poetry, no more exempt than that of thinking, right?

214
00:17:15,160 --> 00:17:22,260
 So, again, I mean, it's about having a true, authentic, you know, the true cabinet maker.

215
00:17:23,120 --> 00:17:23,260
 Right.

216
00:17:23,680 --> 00:17:25,700
 And that's – so, okay.

217
00:17:26,900 --> 00:17:38,360
 For me, I just – I get very resistant when I read – I mean, I literally wrote yuck in the margins of my book next to that.

218
00:17:38,360 --> 00:17:41,320
 But, you know, because, I mean, it does.

219
00:17:41,400 --> 00:17:45,040
 It smells like that kind of like I know the real way.

220
00:17:45,240 --> 00:17:46,880
 Everybody else is doing it wrong.

221
00:17:46,880 --> 00:17:52,960
 And instead of saying, look, instead of making the move where you say, here's the real way everyone else is doing it wrong.

222
00:17:53,020 --> 00:17:57,840
 And by the way, that everyone else thing is doing is just another variation on the thing that I'm talking about.

223
00:17:58,060 --> 00:18:10,880
 That seems like that second move is really, really important that he doesn't make, you know, because for him it really is an inauthentic or it's not real learning if you don't do it in this way.

224
00:18:11,700 --> 00:18:19,600
 And that's where – you know, and he bumps up against the problems all the time of like, well, the machine has buttons and the machine has – when he talks later about the machines.

225
00:18:19,760 --> 00:18:23,220
 And he's like, he just sounds stupid when he talks about technology stuff.

226
00:18:23,240 --> 00:18:25,400
 Yeah, that part was a little weak to me.

227
00:18:25,500 --> 00:18:25,680
 You know?

228
00:18:25,680 --> 00:18:25,860
 Yeah.

229
00:18:26,040 --> 00:18:27,460
 I didn't even know what he was saying.

230
00:18:27,840 --> 00:18:33,180
 Like, what was the intervention into – I mean, I know the machine is bad or something sort of for Heidegger.

231
00:18:33,540 --> 00:18:34,240
 But that part –

232
00:18:34,240 --> 00:18:35,320
 No, the machine is not bad.

233
00:18:35,400 --> 00:18:40,400
 The technological age that allows for the machine to emerge in the way that it does is the problem.

234
00:18:40,400 --> 00:18:48,140
 Well, right, but like the way he articulated the distinction between machinic interactions and then the crap – the woodwork.

235
00:18:48,300 --> 00:18:52,280
 It's like, what – how are you making these – I don't even understand.

236
00:18:52,300 --> 00:18:54,600
 Because the machine doesn't respond to the wood.

237
00:18:54,700 --> 00:18:58,480
 The machine just cuts it in the – you know, at whatever point, right?

238
00:18:58,640 --> 00:18:59,040
 So –

239
00:18:59,040 --> 00:19:00,080
 Right, but the – yeah.

240
00:19:00,080 --> 00:19:03,160
 Which the human could do with hand tools.

241
00:19:03,300 --> 00:19:06,260
 It requires nothing of an industrialized machine.

242
00:19:06,480 --> 00:19:09,720
 It has everything to do with the technological orientation to the thing.

243
00:19:09,800 --> 00:19:13,720
 So, you know, it doesn't matter if, you know, I'm using hand tools.

244
00:19:13,900 --> 00:19:16,680
 It can be technologically applied to the wood.

245
00:19:16,760 --> 00:19:18,860
 And it doesn't matter, frankly, if I'm using machines.

246
00:19:18,860 --> 00:19:20,800
 It could become involved with the –

247
00:19:20,800 --> 00:19:24,140
 See, I don't – I'm not so sure that I buy the second part of that.

248
00:19:24,440 --> 00:19:30,360
 Like, the first part I agree with you, which is that with hand tools, one could still have a technological relationship to the wood.

249
00:19:30,540 --> 00:19:30,940
 Right?

250
00:19:31,000 --> 00:19:33,860
 So, the fact of machinery is not the thing that distinguishes.

251
00:19:34,040 --> 00:19:38,780
 But I'm not sure that with machinery, one could have an authentic relation to the wood for Heidegger.

252
00:19:39,180 --> 00:19:39,720
 You know what I mean?

253
00:19:39,880 --> 00:19:40,660
 I think so.

254
00:19:40,660 --> 00:19:50,160
 I mean, I think so insofar as, you know, if we're going – I know we didn't read the questions concerning technology.

255
00:19:50,520 --> 00:20:00,580
 But I'll kind of bring it in just a little bit where, you know, the major feature that the essence of technology is a revelation of truth.

256
00:20:00,580 --> 00:20:03,420
 It isn't a lathe hour or a disclosure.

257
00:20:04,160 --> 00:20:14,540
 And what he calls sort of like, you know, technological machine techne reveals is the world as a standing reserve.

258
00:20:14,700 --> 00:20:15,220
 That's right.

259
00:20:15,440 --> 00:20:15,560
 Right.

260
00:20:15,880 --> 00:20:22,540
 Which is a way of relating to the world, which is why the hand tools can relate to the world that kind of way.

261
00:20:23,020 --> 00:20:27,000
 But you could imagine – and I don't know, like, maybe Heidegger wouldn't buy this.

262
00:20:27,040 --> 00:20:34,620
 But you could imagine a machinery that isn't oriented – that isn't connected to the world vis-a-vis standing reserve.

263
00:20:35,920 --> 00:20:36,220
 Right.

264
00:20:36,220 --> 00:20:43,620
 So rather than say – and this is where, you know, this is where you would have to probably introduce a bit of multiplicity.

265
00:20:43,740 --> 00:21:02,100
 But rather than look at the power saw as something that is just the bigger, better, faster version of the hand saw, you have to say that the power saw reveals a different relationship to the wood that could break in this direction, could break in that direction.

266
00:21:02,100 --> 00:21:14,660
 Depending on whether or not the wood has been articulated as a extracted resource or something caught up in sort of like, you know, the cusp of human natural affairs.

267
00:21:14,660 --> 00:21:20,760
 I mean, his issue with the machinery also is the context in which it's used, which is the factory.

268
00:21:21,560 --> 00:21:25,760
 And it's an issue – it's a critique of exploitation of labor, right?

269
00:21:25,820 --> 00:21:49,260
 It almost seems related in some way to the master-slave, like, dialectic, where if the worker's only at the level of the slave doing the work, alienated from the entire production, doesn't even know necessarily how the whole product is made, is not invested in it at any moment besides, you know, with the paycheck, then he's not able to have – right, just pulling the lever again and again.

270
00:21:49,880 --> 00:21:53,580
 You don't even have to know what the product is or what it's going to be.

271
00:21:53,700 --> 00:21:55,520
 You just have to be able to do that one task.

272
00:21:55,860 --> 00:22:02,160
 And I guess for Heidegger, that would be inauthentic because you're not involved with the full production of the thing.

273
00:22:02,240 --> 00:22:05,920
 You're not invested in its actualization, right?

274
00:22:05,920 --> 00:22:15,460
 Which if you just added, like, one small clause to that, I would totally buy it, which is to say that is inauthentic woodworking, right?

275
00:22:15,520 --> 00:22:20,280
 Which is to say that the person pulling the lever over and over and over again is not involved with the wood.

276
00:22:20,360 --> 00:22:22,680
 But that's not to say that they aren't involved.

277
00:22:23,000 --> 00:22:27,280
 They're involved with a different – I mean, wood is part of the involvement.

278
00:22:27,280 --> 00:22:36,100
 The wood has been prefigured into a different kind of network that discloses the relationship between all of them just a little bit differently.

279
00:22:36,660 --> 00:22:53,420
 So, like, what I have – the problem that I have with him isn't that there are – that woodworking orients one to wood differently than does mass production, even though they're both being worked with wood.

280
00:22:53,420 --> 00:23:01,920
 It's that woodworking is authentic, whereas business appropriation of wood is not authentic.

281
00:23:02,040 --> 00:23:04,120
 They're both just – they're just – I mean –

282
00:23:04,120 --> 00:23:05,000
 Well, one's external.

283
00:23:05,260 --> 00:23:06,000
 They're different.

284
00:23:06,240 --> 00:23:13,240
 But it's totally – I mean, to me, it resonates with a completely platonic thinking of the simulacrum and copyware.

285
00:23:13,240 --> 00:23:21,360
 You know, the problem with the simulacrum is it integrates external appearance into the interiority of the notion of the model.

286
00:23:21,980 --> 00:23:23,280
 And that's, to me, the same thing.

287
00:23:23,320 --> 00:23:26,120
 It's like it will never be anything but business concerns.

288
00:23:26,520 --> 00:23:33,460
 You know, any occupation without that relatedness, relatedness to the wood itself, the craft will never be anything but empty, busy work.

289
00:23:33,520 --> 00:23:41,820
 Any occupation with it will be determined exclusively by business concerns, the idea that business concerns are exterior to working with wood.

290
00:23:42,600 --> 00:23:44,180
 And it's like that's what you're doing.

291
00:23:44,260 --> 00:23:48,400
 You're bringing in the exteriority of a relation to channel through your relationship to the object.

292
00:23:48,680 --> 00:23:53,720
 And to me, that's just Plato's simulacrum copy model distinction.

293
00:23:54,360 --> 00:23:56,760
 Everything is potentially empty, busy work.

294
00:23:57,540 --> 00:23:58,060
 Like, you know what I mean?

295
00:23:58,120 --> 00:24:03,000
 Like, why is it – the framing the whole – I mean, basically, the whole project in the language of authenticity

296
00:24:03,000 --> 00:24:04,160
 seems strange to me.

297
00:24:04,260 --> 00:24:06,200
 It's like certain things suck.

298
00:24:06,460 --> 00:24:10,840
 Like, working in a factory sucks, but it's not inauthentic to me.

299
00:24:11,100 --> 00:24:11,680
 You know what I mean?

300
00:24:11,700 --> 00:24:20,600
 It's like I don't know why you have to evaluate the different contexts and then uphold the supposedly authentic one.

301
00:24:20,680 --> 00:24:21,560
 You don't have to.

302
00:24:21,840 --> 00:24:22,980
 But I feel like –

303
00:24:22,980 --> 00:24:23,560
 Well, Heidegger does.

304
00:24:23,560 --> 00:24:25,460
 But my sense is that Heidegger consistently does.

305
00:24:25,840 --> 00:24:26,240
 For sure.

306
00:24:26,240 --> 00:24:30,240
 Let me just say, I mean, in this context, like – this was several weeks ago.

307
00:24:30,300 --> 00:24:35,060
 I watched this video on YouTube on a Japanese company's tuna.

308
00:24:37,120 --> 00:24:41,160
 I just got interested in tuna and how it gets manufactured, right?

309
00:24:41,520 --> 00:24:43,060
 Like, and I watched this.

310
00:24:43,140 --> 00:24:44,140
 It's an 18-minute video.

311
00:24:44,260 --> 00:24:47,040
 I'm going to send – I'll send you guys the link because it's really extraordinary.

312
00:24:47,040 --> 00:24:55,260
 And I just never had any sense of the scale and scope of the process of eating tuna, right?

313
00:24:55,700 --> 00:24:57,420
 Like, I eat a lot of fresh tuna here.

314
00:24:57,480 --> 00:24:58,540
 That's what got me interested in it.

315
00:24:58,600 --> 00:25:03,960
 It's like, I wonder – you know, like, my neighbors catch tuna and they give me chunks of tuna and I eat fresh tuna.

316
00:25:04,040 --> 00:25:07,480
 And I'm like, I wonder how that relates to the stuff that we get in the store.

317
00:25:08,020 --> 00:25:09,400
 And it shows you the process.

318
00:25:09,400 --> 00:25:14,500
 And, again, this is like one sort of small – not even small, but one Japanese company's.

319
00:25:14,840 --> 00:25:24,560
 And it's from the moment of catching the fish and the incredible circuitry through which the fish go in order to arrive, like, on your grocery store.

320
00:25:24,560 --> 00:25:28,740
 I mean, it's – I had two simultaneous reactions in watching it.

321
00:25:29,060 --> 00:25:41,320
 One was absolute horror at the, like, incredibly – I don't know, just – the sheer brutality at every point in this.

322
00:25:41,420 --> 00:25:44,760
 And it really – like, this is the Heideggerian sort of part.

323
00:25:44,760 --> 00:25:56,280
 Like, it is absolutely so fucking violent at every step in this process and yet its violence is very hidden.

324
00:25:56,440 --> 00:25:58,860
 It's just like, oh, it's now just a frozen piece of meat.

325
00:25:58,980 --> 00:26:07,080
 So, you know, you cut it and the worker does his, you know, cutting and then it moves to the next layer on the really conveyor belt, right?

326
00:26:07,560 --> 00:26:12,140
 And it's packaged in this way and it's cut in this way and all this sort of stuff, like this incredible brutality.

327
00:26:12,140 --> 00:26:17,180
 But also the extraordinary fascination that I had with, like, what a species, man.

328
00:26:17,580 --> 00:26:20,520
 What a species that can set up a process.

329
00:26:20,800 --> 00:26:25,780
 Like, we talk about things like mass production, but we rarely see it, right?

330
00:26:25,840 --> 00:26:35,620
 And just to see mass production on that scale and just be like, I had no idea how extraordinarily complex, sophisticated –

331
00:26:35,620 --> 00:26:41,060
 like, these machines are built very specifically for very certain size fish that are shaped in particular ways.

332
00:26:41,060 --> 00:26:52,060
 I mean, just the whole – all of the apparatus that goes from massive shipping boats to, you know, the instant freeze that they have to do to the cutting up to the packaging to the – like, all this stuff.

333
00:26:52,120 --> 00:26:59,440
 And I'm just like, this is – it's both – it's mind-blowing in its extraordinary scope and both positively and negatively.

334
00:26:59,660 --> 00:27:03,620
 Like, I really had that simultaneous reaction and I feel like he only has the negative part.

335
00:27:03,740 --> 00:27:10,000
 Like, there's no part of him that's just like, that's pretty incredible that this species called humans has set this up.

336
00:27:10,000 --> 00:27:26,840
 On the one hand, all technological process like that is a disclosure.

337
00:27:27,100 --> 00:27:32,400
 Everything from the massive tuna factory to the woodworking.

338
00:27:32,540 --> 00:27:33,540
 They're both techniques, right?

339
00:27:33,540 --> 00:27:38,480
 They both disclose the world in a particular kind of way.

340
00:27:39,560 --> 00:27:44,980
 But the mechanized one is how they disclose, right?

341
00:27:45,060 --> 00:27:47,620
 I mean, they really are like styles of disclosure.

342
00:27:47,880 --> 00:27:54,360
 Like, how – you know, even despite the fact that, you know, many of the relationships contain the same elements, right?

343
00:27:54,360 --> 00:28:08,760
 The way that each one is configured within that relationship and the sort of subtraction of some of those elements and the addition of other elements configures the world as resource, as nothing more than resource.

344
00:28:08,760 --> 00:28:24,400
 And that's the thing that he's bulking against is the reduction of anything to extractable resource that has no other sets of relationships beyond the one.

345
00:28:24,520 --> 00:28:27,520
 And speeding anything up for Hayager seems like a problem, too.

346
00:28:27,620 --> 00:28:32,580
 Like, he even critiques abbreviations like U for university.

347
00:28:32,580 --> 00:28:43,720
 Like, somehow that kind of technologizing of language reflects on the speed of thinking or the advancement of society in a negative way.

348
00:28:44,140 --> 00:28:46,700
 And it's like, what do you want us to do?

349
00:28:46,800 --> 00:28:53,920
 Like, it seems like – I mean, modern society is obviously super invested in efficiency.

350
00:28:53,920 --> 00:29:02,840
 And the reason that we all have an easy access to goods and services is because of that, you know, technological progress.

351
00:29:03,020 --> 00:29:05,960
 Like, the reason we can go to grocery stores and get a steak –

352
00:29:05,960 --> 00:29:06,480
 And get tuna fish.

353
00:29:06,580 --> 00:29:11,060
 And get tuna fish, get whatever, is because of that highly complex system.

354
00:29:11,720 --> 00:29:17,860
 And – but people do value some sort of authentic relation to land and food.

355
00:29:17,860 --> 00:29:24,460
 And – but the only way that you can then access that kind of lifestyle is if you already have money or means.

356
00:29:24,560 --> 00:29:30,800
 You can't just – like, there's this show, Bobby Flay, you know, the cook or the chef, and Giada.

357
00:29:30,920 --> 00:29:32,420
 Bobby and Giada go to Italy.

358
00:29:32,860 --> 00:29:37,760
 And it's like – and they romanticize because in Italy, you can source all of your ingredients.

359
00:29:37,760 --> 00:29:44,880
 So you can go to the farm, the farmer's market, wherever, just your neighbor and get everything and make it that day.

360
00:29:44,880 --> 00:29:49,060
 And make your pasta and your fucking whatever and get your tomatoes and all that shit.

361
00:29:49,380 --> 00:29:54,680
 And it's like, okay, maybe a person can do that in Italy that's not rich.

362
00:29:54,820 --> 00:29:59,300
 But the point is, Bobby and Giada can do that, who are both millionaires.

363
00:29:59,580 --> 00:30:02,080
 You know, not – not everyone can do that in America.

364
00:30:02,200 --> 00:30:09,380
 And it's not their fault that they're using mechanized processes to access their food or whatever.

365
00:30:09,540 --> 00:30:09,960
 I don't know.

366
00:30:10,260 --> 00:30:12,660
 Well, I don't think it's minimally expensive to be poor.

367
00:30:13,180 --> 00:30:13,620
 Exactly.

368
00:30:14,140 --> 00:30:19,140
 You can be more, like, fastidious and discerning with your money when you have that.

369
00:30:19,460 --> 00:30:27,320
 I can, like, go get the cheap ingredients because I have the time and leisure and sort of educational background and, you know, lack of other pressing concerns.

370
00:30:27,560 --> 00:30:27,680
 Right.

371
00:30:27,800 --> 00:30:30,480
 I don't think Heidegger would – I think Heidegger would agree with you.

372
00:30:30,560 --> 00:30:33,540
 Not that it's – you know, he wouldn't say that it's their fault.

373
00:30:33,660 --> 00:30:38,760
 He's like, look, this is a symptom of the cultural, you know, transformation.

374
00:30:39,820 --> 00:30:43,140
 And he doesn't – you know, it's not necessarily exploitation for him.

375
00:30:43,140 --> 00:31:00,220
 Like, his interest is much more ethical than it is Marxist, than it is political in that regard, which is just like – I mean, what you're doing is you're just – you know, what humanity tends to do is it creates this inauthentic relationship to object worlds, which is how you get objects.

376
00:31:00,720 --> 00:31:00,840
 Right.

377
00:31:00,840 --> 00:31:12,160
 So, I think the critique such as – and there is – I mean, I think there's pretty clearly a critique – is really about a Weltanschauung, right?

378
00:31:12,240 --> 00:31:16,420
 Like, it's just kind of – this is the – this is how we live now.

379
00:31:16,880 --> 00:31:25,100
 And so, you know, that's to me – and this is the best I can do when I'm reading Heidegger oftentimes is to start thinking, well, there really isn't a good guy.

380
00:31:25,460 --> 00:31:32,120
 Like, that sort of – the handy – not that there really isn't a bad guy because there's absolutely a fucking bad guy.

381
00:31:32,180 --> 00:31:35,040
 And that's the sort of utilitarian technologization.

382
00:31:35,900 --> 00:31:38,960
 But the good guy is also a version of this.

383
00:31:38,960 --> 00:31:44,760
 So, what I can – what I get out of Heidegger, you know, is that there isn't just a hand craftsman.

384
00:31:44,860 --> 00:31:50,640
 There can't be a hand craftsman of the wood who is truly just responding to the wood.

385
00:31:50,880 --> 00:31:57,100
 That every kind of response is differently and inauthentic and not true.

386
00:31:57,200 --> 00:32:00,300
 That's why we're not thinking, by the way, just to – not to give it away.

387
00:32:01,180 --> 00:32:04,200
 Like, you know, we can't get there, right?

388
00:32:04,280 --> 00:32:06,880
 We cannot get to that sort of disclosive.

389
00:32:06,880 --> 00:32:23,440
 And that's the sort of – whether you attribute it to, I mean, historical transformation or a species-wide characteristic, that we're just not capable because everything is extracted as standing reserve, as propositions, as contents.

390
00:32:24,140 --> 00:32:26,860
 That's just our disposition to things.

391
00:32:31,180 --> 00:32:31,880
 That's what we're doing.

392
00:32:31,880 --> 00:32:34,880
 That's what we're doing.

393
00:32:34,880 --> 00:32:46,060
 Heidegger is the guy, even more than Derek, I feel like, who's taught me about the importance of – we talked about the episode we just released on indirection and intimacy.

394
00:32:46,540 --> 00:32:48,080
 That's his whole thing, right?

395
00:32:48,100 --> 00:32:52,700
 His whole sort of serial indirection, which is just like, hey, we're going to try a path.

396
00:32:52,800 --> 00:32:57,880
 We're going to see – and we can't – I mean, there's even a quote on it where it says, the question – this is on 21.

397
00:32:57,880 --> 00:33:06,920
 The question, what is called thinking, can never be answered by proposing a definition of the concept thinking and then diligently explaining what is contained in that definition, right?

398
00:33:07,060 --> 00:33:12,940
 Like, which would be the usual way of understanding how to answer the question, what is called thinking.

399
00:33:13,040 --> 00:33:25,140
 Like, I feel as if – for me, at least, I learned from Heidegger more than anyone that in order to respond to a question, it's not always by answering it, right, in the conventional sense.

400
00:33:25,180 --> 00:33:29,780
 It is by following different trajectories that come out of it.

401
00:33:30,440 --> 00:33:35,280
 And Heidegger, like I said, more than anyone else, just shows – like, what is called thinking?

402
00:33:35,280 --> 00:33:43,260
 Okay, well, I could just define the term and explain what I mean, but that is not – there are reasons why I'm not doing that.

403
00:33:45,060 --> 00:33:49,580
 And, I mean, I think actually for podcast listeners, that's a huge point, right?

404
00:33:49,620 --> 00:33:58,760
 Like, it's a huge point to say simply answering a question is not always the most fruitful or interesting way of engaging the question.

405
00:33:59,640 --> 00:34:11,880
 I mean, I think one gets that from the platonic dialogues in terms of the sophists versus, you know, versus Socrates, where Socrates wants an answer, you know, and the sophists want long-winded speeches.

406
00:34:12,420 --> 00:34:21,820
 And Socrates' aversion to this is precisely, like, questions are supposed to have answers, you know, and the sophists are like, that's one way of responding to questions.

407
00:34:22,560 --> 00:34:28,220
 And, you know, in Heidegger's case, it's the least interesting, you know, and I tend to agree.

408
00:34:28,840 --> 00:34:41,700
 So, I mean, although, you know, Socrates' desire for answers is not to – like, generally when we're talking about, look, the desire for an answer is to remedy the question.

409
00:34:41,760 --> 00:34:42,140
 That's right.

410
00:34:42,240 --> 00:34:43,040
 He's not agreeing.

411
00:34:43,260 --> 00:34:51,620
 Like, it's like, you know, assuaging a wound or, like, you know, putting salve on the wound so I don't have to deal with it anymore.

412
00:34:52,240 --> 00:35:02,260
 And, you know, Socrates' orientation to questions, which he does want answers to, or at least responses, and they need to come, you know, in pretty – like, he gives pretty tight –

413
00:35:02,260 --> 00:35:03,500
 It's yes or nos, man.

414
00:35:03,540 --> 00:35:04,180
 He doesn't want –

415
00:35:04,180 --> 00:35:04,880
 It's yes or no.

416
00:35:04,940 --> 00:35:05,140
 Yeah.

417
00:35:05,580 --> 00:35:05,900
 Right?

418
00:35:06,300 --> 00:35:10,300
 But the answer, the yes or the no, propels that machinery.

419
00:35:10,640 --> 00:35:10,680
 That's right.

420
00:35:10,680 --> 00:35:17,060
 So the function of the answer is to lead to – is to allow for the next question to be formulated based on.

421
00:35:17,060 --> 00:35:18,580
 It does not halt the inquiry.

422
00:35:18,860 --> 00:35:26,100
 Like, we've – okay, we've now arrived – no, it just propels it to the next sort of, you know, elaboration.

423
00:35:26,240 --> 00:35:28,040
 I mean, you're certainly right about that.

424
00:35:28,440 --> 00:35:29,220
 When – yeah.

425
00:35:29,620 --> 00:35:35,660
 And when searching for definitions, you know, like, what is thinking, that's not the title of the book, right?

426
00:35:35,820 --> 00:35:35,980
 Right.

427
00:35:36,200 --> 00:35:39,500
 It's what – he doesn't title it Voss Ist Danken.

428
00:35:39,660 --> 00:35:46,800
 It's Voss Heist Danken, which is a strange – it's a kind of an awkward – at least in the translation, an awkward phrasing.

429
00:35:46,800 --> 00:35:50,540
 But it seems important, the distinction between the two, right?

430
00:35:50,580 --> 00:35:57,100
 Because, I mean, he's not – would you say that he's deferring the question of the essence of thinking throughout this book?

431
00:35:57,360 --> 00:35:57,840
 I mean, because –

432
00:35:57,840 --> 00:36:00,740
 Well, there is the is there, but, like, the heist is interesting.

433
00:36:00,800 --> 00:36:01,400
 What is it called?

434
00:36:01,720 --> 00:36:01,800
 Yeah.

435
00:36:01,800 --> 00:36:04,160
 You would, like – it's not even just what is it called.

436
00:36:04,280 --> 00:36:07,940
 I mean, in German, if – that's how you would ask somebody's name.

437
00:36:08,160 --> 00:36:08,560
 Exactly.

438
00:36:08,740 --> 00:36:16,540
 It makes German interesting in that way because you would say, like, who are you or whatever, which just in the grammar of it suggests an

439
00:36:16,540 --> 00:36:17,660
 essence of being.

440
00:36:17,780 --> 00:36:25,400
 But in German, it's V. Heistu, which is what are you called, which calls attention that it's a linguistic operation.

441
00:36:25,840 --> 00:36:27,500
 What are you called in this language?

442
00:36:28,040 --> 00:36:34,580
 And it's the same thing with the title of this book, which he doesn't talk about the language precisely in these lectures.

443
00:36:34,580 --> 00:36:38,600
 But clearly, language is the house of being and we dwell in language.

444
00:36:38,720 --> 00:36:45,900
 All of that is classic Heidegger and points to that kind of – that sort of relational sensibility.

445
00:36:46,040 --> 00:36:53,480
 It's always – there's a – I don't know if he ever uses the language of mediation, you know, in the Hegelian sense.

446
00:36:53,600 --> 00:37:00,760
 But language is clearly key and thinking is an immediative force in some way, right?

447
00:37:00,920 --> 00:37:01,700
 So –

448
00:37:01,700 --> 00:37:07,300
 And the other inflection of the Vos Heist is that that's how you would ask, like, a translation question.

449
00:37:07,420 --> 00:37:08,460
 You'd say, like, what does it mean?

450
00:37:09,100 --> 00:37:09,320
 Right.

451
00:37:09,800 --> 00:37:12,620
 Vos Heist Denken would be, like, what does thinking mean?

452
00:37:13,200 --> 00:37:17,420
 So, I mean, that's another inflection point of instead of Vos ist, you know.

453
00:37:18,040 --> 00:37:18,220
 Right.

454
00:37:18,860 --> 00:37:20,140
 And I think that you're right.

455
00:37:20,200 --> 00:37:26,180
 Like, it is that sense of – it's not simply a question of providing a definition or an answer.

456
00:37:26,320 --> 00:37:31,780
 And not just because he's a philosopher, right, and wants to avoid and wants to discourse more, whatever.

457
00:37:31,780 --> 00:37:37,820
 But it is an attempt to model the movement of thinking that is the sort of – I don't know.

458
00:37:37,900 --> 00:37:44,720
 You could call it perpetual withdrawal or you could call it perpetual deferral or you could call it the sort of serial production of responses.

459
00:37:44,940 --> 00:37:51,280
 That's my preference, right, is that the sort of – like, we're going to try this and then this and then this and then this.

460
00:37:51,360 --> 00:37:56,160
 The series approach to thinking.

461
00:37:57,520 --> 00:37:58,920
 But I don't know.

462
00:37:58,920 --> 00:38:09,680
 I mean, I just think that it's important not to – my aversion there is to this – to the idea that an answer ever is an answer.

463
00:38:10,380 --> 00:38:17,060
 And because that's what I would always want to do is to say, like, that content where they just provide a definition of thinking and say, here's what it is.

464
00:38:17,100 --> 00:38:18,220
 Here's our operational definition.

465
00:38:18,620 --> 00:38:22,560
 It doesn't actually operate as ending the conversation either, right?

466
00:38:22,680 --> 00:38:24,980
 Like, it – now, pragmatically it might.

467
00:38:25,060 --> 00:38:26,040
 People are like, okay, got it.

468
00:38:26,080 --> 00:38:26,780
 I'm out, right?

469
00:38:26,820 --> 00:38:28,360
 Like, I don't need any more.

470
00:38:28,360 --> 00:38:30,080
 But of course you do, right?

471
00:38:30,120 --> 00:38:36,460
 You have to have that definition played out in circumstances and then you always say, well, does it apply to this or does it apply to that?

472
00:38:36,680 --> 00:38:49,460
 So the aversion to a definition to me, just like his aversion to the machines and these things, these things need to be maybe just more deftly managed than he tends to manage them.

473
00:38:49,460 --> 00:39:03,300
 He does offer – he offers sort of a weak, like, not really an apology, but like where he says the critique of these kinds of thinking, it's more of a diagnosis than a dismissive gesture.

474
00:39:03,300 --> 00:39:12,520
 He says, like, in order for science to operate, it needs these categories, so it's not really the fault of science that it's operating this way.

475
00:39:13,120 --> 00:39:15,300
 And yet, there is a fault there.

476
00:39:15,780 --> 00:39:21,000
 Like, it's not accessing the complexity or the relationality that I'm after.

477
00:39:21,640 --> 00:39:26,480
 So it's sort of a necessity and possibility, like, binary there.

478
00:39:26,480 --> 00:39:27,140
 Yeah, yeah.

479
00:39:27,140 --> 00:39:28,200
 But I think you're right, though.

480
00:39:28,260 --> 00:39:31,200
 Like, he doesn't – it's not that satisfying for me, at least.

481
00:39:31,280 --> 00:39:40,100
 It feels like more of a, you know, something on the side that he's just like, well, I could foresee your critique, something like this, so this is why I'm putting it here.

482
00:39:40,280 --> 00:39:42,920
 But I really don't mean that, you know.

483
00:39:43,860 --> 00:39:50,540
 Although there's an interesting – I do think – I'd be curious, particularly for you, Nate, and your inclination towards the Hegelian move.

484
00:39:50,740 --> 00:39:58,400
 Like, if he didn't hold out this notion of the true thinking and the true teaching and the true – you know, the authentic or whatever.

485
00:39:59,200 --> 00:39:59,380
 Yeah.

486
00:39:59,480 --> 00:40:09,600
 If you didn't hold out that – and by the way, I do think that in each case, those things are going to get problematized later on so that they were not as clearly the good guys as opposed to the bad guys.

487
00:40:10,280 --> 00:40:23,400
 But to me, it actually feels a lot like Hegel in the sense of, like, it is a kind of relentless – not negation in the sense, but it is a relentless, like, there's no good way out of this.

488
00:40:23,580 --> 00:40:25,100
 There is no solution.

489
00:40:25,480 --> 00:40:26,380
 There is no answer.

490
00:40:26,640 --> 00:40:28,720
 But I'm setting it up as if there is.

491
00:40:29,080 --> 00:40:34,400
 I'm setting those up as if true thinking is this, and all the rest is utilitarian calculus.

492
00:40:34,700 --> 00:40:39,280
 And where I'm going to go is to say, like, actually, that true thinking is impossible.

493
00:40:39,880 --> 00:40:41,640
 That's why it withdraws, right?

494
00:40:41,800 --> 00:40:49,700
 Like, I mean, given its nature is withdrawal, you can't arrive at – you're never going to get to the point where you're like, ah, I truly thought.

495
00:40:50,380 --> 00:40:52,020
 Like, it's just not going to happen.

496
00:40:52,620 --> 00:40:54,640
 But you don't realize that on the front end.

497
00:40:54,660 --> 00:41:00,940
 On the front end, you think, okay, there's some true thinking, and I could possibly be a true thinker instead of a utilitarian calculator.

498
00:41:01,640 --> 00:41:02,180
 You're right.

499
00:41:02,180 --> 00:41:08,220
 I mean, he does basically admit – like, even I, Heidegger, the great Heidegger, I never access true thinking.

500
00:41:08,540 --> 00:41:13,580
 Like, and so I'm culpable in this just as anybody else is, just as the sciences are, et cetera.

501
00:41:13,760 --> 00:41:18,280
 But the distinction – he does posit alternatives, like, throughout.

502
00:41:18,600 --> 00:41:21,380
 And he'll complicate them, but there's the poetic.

503
00:41:21,580 --> 00:41:26,900
 The poetic is often phrased as a kind of panacea, basically.

504
00:41:27,140 --> 00:41:28,920
 Some sort of – again, it's on the horizon.

505
00:41:29,520 --> 00:41:35,760
 But it's something that's posed as an explicit alternative to humanist categories of thinking.

506
00:41:36,320 --> 00:41:39,860
 And the difference between that and Hegel is that Hegel never offers an alternative.

507
00:41:40,380 --> 00:41:43,040
 All you have are subject-object relations.

508
00:41:43,200 --> 00:41:47,180
 And again, they're reductive, but you don't get out of that reductive apparatus.

509
00:41:47,880 --> 00:41:51,440
 For Heidegger, there's at least a desire for an alternative, right?

510
00:41:51,580 --> 00:41:55,160
 And so Hegel, like, literally just refuses to offer that.

511
00:41:55,160 --> 00:42:00,100
 And I like that for very specific reasons, and I can see why He wouldn't like that, clearly.

512
00:42:00,420 --> 00:42:05,240
 Well, he kind of holds out a certain kind of hope for that alternative.

513
00:42:05,680 --> 00:42:12,400
 I mean, when he sort of gestures toward truth and, I mean, especially Aletheia as a kind of clearing,

514
00:42:12,500 --> 00:42:17,960
 a kind of disclosure that is imbued with a multiplicity of possibilities, right?

515
00:42:17,960 --> 00:42:26,380
 That, you know, depending on the kind of network of relations that, you know, makes this clearing,

516
00:42:26,480 --> 00:42:31,440
 this clearing, and that clearing, that clearing, then, you know, it can go in a number of different directions.

517
00:42:31,800 --> 00:42:36,500
 And in that – on the, you know, the penultimate page of the second lecture,

518
00:42:36,600 --> 00:42:38,880
 when he's talking about the problem of one-track thinking,

519
00:42:39,840 --> 00:42:46,880
 and he's got, you know, this really particular technological way of thinking about one-track thinking,

520
00:42:47,020 --> 00:42:48,560
 I'll just read it here quickly.

521
00:42:49,140 --> 00:42:56,760
 This is where he's basically telling his – this is in the – every lecture ends with this little bit called

522
00:42:56,760 --> 00:43:01,400
 Summary and Transition, and it's – you can tell that, you know, he's had a conversation with his class.

523
00:43:01,460 --> 00:43:04,560
 These are lectures that he's giving in class, and he's had a conversation with his students,

524
00:43:04,560 --> 00:43:09,100
 and he's, you know, probably fielded a few questions, and then he's kind of, like,

525
00:43:09,620 --> 00:43:14,300
 summarizing what's happened and sort of, like, clarifying some things that happened in the conversation and elsewhere.

526
00:43:14,740 --> 00:43:18,420
 And this is right after he's kind of, like – well, actually sandwiched in between,

527
00:43:18,780 --> 00:43:22,940
 where he's kind of, like, almost chastising some of his students for getting it wrong.

528
00:43:23,020 --> 00:43:27,040
 It's like, I never said Socrates was the only great thinker, right?

529
00:43:27,040 --> 00:43:29,240
 I said he was the purest thinker.

530
00:43:29,360 --> 00:43:31,020
 Purity is different than greatness.

531
00:43:32,180 --> 00:43:40,320
 And he is really – I mean, that – just as an aside, he is really careful of his terminology in ways that we aren't being right now,

532
00:43:40,420 --> 00:43:43,740
 you know, and so it's easy to say, oh, he says this guy's better.

533
00:43:43,820 --> 00:43:45,600
 He's like, he's not saying he's better.

534
00:43:45,720 --> 00:43:46,560
 He's saying he's perfect.

535
00:43:46,720 --> 00:43:48,160
 That's different for him, but sorry.

536
00:43:48,740 --> 00:43:48,940
 Yeah.

537
00:43:49,580 --> 00:43:55,900
 But right before that, it's like right before that part and right after he's talking about the importance of listening.

538
00:43:56,340 --> 00:43:57,680
 You stupid students, listen up.

539
00:44:00,180 --> 00:44:01,540
 And here's what he's got.

540
00:44:01,600 --> 00:44:03,700
 This is the first full paragraph on 26.

541
00:44:04,860 --> 00:44:12,620
 On the other hand, you will make close listening essentially easier for yourselves if you will rid yourself in time of a habit,

542
00:44:12,760 --> 00:44:14,340
 which I shall call one-track thinking.

543
00:44:14,500 --> 00:44:16,120
 I just so want to say that to my students.

544
00:44:16,440 --> 00:44:23,540
 It'll be so much easier for you to understand the genius of what I am telling you if you just were stopped being one-track thinkers.

545
00:44:24,180 --> 00:44:28,220
 But anyway, no arrogance there.

546
00:44:28,860 --> 00:44:29,160
 Right.

547
00:44:30,120 --> 00:44:37,340
 But then, you know, like it sounds totally arrogant and shitty there, and then, you know, it'll get muddled here a bit.

548
00:44:37,340 --> 00:44:44,580
 The dominion of this manner of perception is so vast today that our eyes can barely encompass it.

549
00:44:44,900 --> 00:44:50,400
 The expression one-track has been chosen on purpose because I'm careful with my terminology.

550
00:44:51,680 --> 00:44:55,700
 We should – track has to do with rails and rails with technology.

551
00:44:55,700 --> 00:45:05,340
 We would be making matters too easy for ourselves if we simply took the view that the dominion of one-track thinking has grown out of human laziness.

552
00:45:05,880 --> 00:45:17,700
 This one-track thinking, which is becoming ever more widespread in various shapes, is one of those unsuspected and inconspicuous forms mentioned earlier in which the essence of technology assumes dominion,

553
00:45:18,540 --> 00:45:22,900
 because that essence will and therefore needs absolute univocity.

554
00:45:23,000 --> 00:45:25,920
 So it's not, you know, stupid, lazy students.

555
00:45:26,040 --> 00:45:28,280
 You're one-track thinking because you can't do any better.

556
00:45:28,280 --> 00:45:35,720
 It's because the essence of technology is such that it directs intellectual engagement within –

557
00:45:35,720 --> 00:45:36,340
 It's endemic.

558
00:45:36,340 --> 00:45:36,900
 It's endemic.

559
00:45:37,500 --> 00:45:39,600
 Sequential orientation.

560
00:45:40,540 --> 00:45:56,160
 But – so this is kind of, you know, building off of what both you and John and Nate have been talking about is that I think there is this sort of yearning for a kind of notion of thinking or a style of thinking that is less linear,

561
00:45:56,360 --> 00:46:02,780
 that finds itself in this clearing that is imbued with possibilities that could be taken in a number of different directions.

562
00:46:02,780 --> 00:46:16,480
 And part of what he balks at a technologicized version of thinking or scientific kind of thinking is almost like a platonic, almost like that dialectical kind of thinking.

563
00:46:16,600 --> 00:46:19,680
 It's like it could only move forward in one direction.

564
00:46:19,860 --> 00:46:23,920
 And what he finds there is a smothering univocity.

565
00:46:23,920 --> 00:46:36,220
 And I, you know, immediately my allergy and reaction to that is to think that, you know, one-track thinking is not one as you might think.

566
00:46:36,460 --> 00:46:43,920
 That every iteration of that serial progression is there – it's going to diverge in really weird ways.

567
00:46:44,920 --> 00:46:54,440
 That the addition of something new, you know, is going to – like, in other words, that, you know, that linearity is not as constraining as it might seem.

568
00:46:54,680 --> 00:46:58,640
 I wonder how Heidegger would sound differently after performativity, you know?

569
00:46:58,800 --> 00:47:02,860
 Like if he'd had the conceptual framework of performativity – I mean, he didn't.

570
00:47:02,940 --> 00:47:09,060
 He wasn't alive during, you know, the sort of Austin, Wittgenstein, whatever.

571
00:47:09,060 --> 00:47:12,640
 But – because he doesn't think – he doesn't quite go.

572
00:47:13,020 --> 00:47:15,520
 But it does seem like – I mean, I'm with you, Nathaniel.

573
00:47:15,600 --> 00:47:17,480
 Like everything seems to want to go there.

574
00:47:17,600 --> 00:47:21,480
 And yet he still – it still just seems like he must have.

575
00:47:22,360 --> 00:47:23,020
 It's sort of there.

576
00:47:23,080 --> 00:47:29,340
 I mean, I find like the unconscious as a conceptual thing throughout this.

577
00:47:29,400 --> 00:47:32,420
 I mean, withdrawal – or maybe non-conscious, right?

578
00:47:32,420 --> 00:47:43,460
 I mean, performativity is all about sort of non-conscious habitualizations of, you know, social or political or economic imperatives, right?

579
00:47:43,520 --> 00:47:45,440
 So it's like I see that here.

580
00:47:45,580 --> 00:47:47,540
 I mean, clearly he doesn't have the word for it.

581
00:47:47,840 --> 00:47:51,020
 But to me, it's like performativity is almost the bad thing, right?

582
00:47:51,500 --> 00:47:56,480
 Or at least a version of performativity where you enact humanist categories is the bad thing.

583
00:47:56,480 --> 00:47:58,060
 OK, so that's the thing.

584
00:47:58,280 --> 00:48:03,840
 But it's like it's – for me, what I mean when I say performativity is that the enactment precedes the subject, right?

585
00:48:03,920 --> 00:48:07,160
 Like there is – the action comes first.

586
00:48:07,380 --> 00:48:17,320
 And he's interested in – and to that extent, it can't possibly be utilitarian calculus because there would be nothing to utilitarianize, right?

587
00:48:17,480 --> 00:48:19,600
 Because there's no sort of subject.

588
00:48:19,600 --> 00:48:24,500
 There is an action and then residually the big idea of a subject, you know.

589
00:48:25,140 --> 00:48:45,600
 I'll push back on that a bit because I think precisely his concern is the action of calculus preceding the subject because it is constitutive of a particular kind of subjectivity and relatedness to the world, which is why it's not because you're lazy or because, you know, you're doing the wrong things.

590
00:48:45,600 --> 00:48:56,200
 It's because your involvement is essentially with a calculating – within, you know, the performative of calculus.

591
00:48:56,460 --> 00:48:56,640
 Right.

592
00:48:56,740 --> 00:48:58,260
 But you're absolutely right.

593
00:48:58,360 --> 00:49:07,680
 So what's being made here is subjects – that's why no one is being lazy is because they're being made by a sort of process that trains him to think in this particular way.

594
00:49:07,680 --> 00:49:11,780
 But what he can't do is get to the sort of serial differential responses.

595
00:49:12,440 --> 00:49:16,120
 That's what I mean because it's just like, well, all of that is going to be inauthentic.

596
00:49:16,600 --> 00:49:20,680
 And even the thing that I held out the hope as being authentic is still going to end up being inauthentic.

597
00:49:21,320 --> 00:49:34,900
 And it's like that to me is like what is so appealing about the Nietzschean-Delouzian register is that all you can do in the face with perpetual inauthenticity is say none of it's inauthentic.

598
00:49:35,440 --> 00:49:35,640
 Right.

599
00:49:35,720 --> 00:49:44,140
 Like it is just a series of serial differential responses that there's not a question of one being true thinking anymore.

600
00:49:44,280 --> 00:49:50,460
 I mean we're past that point, I think, historically, conceptually of saying this is real thinking.

601
00:49:50,900 --> 00:49:51,640
 That's not.

602
00:49:52,280 --> 00:49:52,580
 Yeah.

603
00:49:52,760 --> 00:49:56,320
 And he can't get there and that's really what I meant.

604
00:49:56,980 --> 00:49:57,440
 It's weird.

605
00:49:57,680 --> 00:49:57,940
 Yeah.

606
00:49:58,340 --> 00:50:05,980
 Everything seems to be straining towards that, but it's also constrained by – and I know I'm using his kind of language, right?

607
00:50:05,980 --> 00:50:16,920
 But it's constrained by his holding on to the notion of the true and the authentic, even though that true and authentic and those essences are not going to function the way that they previously did.

608
00:50:17,500 --> 00:50:26,460
 It seems like a conceptual regress from Nietzsche and even from Hegel to me, at least when you think about it in those terms.

609
00:50:26,460 --> 00:50:38,480
 Like he seems to be desiring some kind of reality that we can hold on to or an authentic relation, whatever you want to call it, that has been made inaccessible by modernity, right?

610
00:50:38,520 --> 00:50:42,740
 I mean his fetishizing of the Greeks to me is part of that as well.

611
00:50:42,840 --> 00:50:45,360
 It's like they had an authentic relation.

612
00:50:45,660 --> 00:50:47,180
 It's like how do you know that?

613
00:50:47,500 --> 00:50:52,720
 You were accessing the Greeks through thousands of years of mediation.

614
00:50:53,340 --> 00:50:54,880
 There's no authentic relation.

615
00:50:55,040 --> 00:51:06,080
 Even if they posed one through their texts, how do you know they were living authentically and how can you pose their way of living as a horizon of our being either?

616
00:51:06,400 --> 00:51:13,920
 So what you have to do is say he doesn't know that and he knows that he doesn't know that and he is positing a differential.

617
00:51:13,920 --> 00:51:21,380
 I mean he is – that to me is the generous read, which Nathaniel has been offering so far, which Nathaniel – that's become the role that you've assumed.

618
00:51:21,520 --> 00:51:26,040
 You're like I'm going to do the affirmative reading for everything, which is great.

619
00:51:26,240 --> 00:51:26,920
 I mean it really is.

620
00:51:26,920 --> 00:51:27,420
 No, it's good.

621
00:51:28,800 --> 00:51:33,280
 It's very, very important because otherwise we're just going to sit around and be like, yeah, this authenticity crap, you know.

622
00:51:34,800 --> 00:51:38,080
 And it reminds – at least for me, it's incredibly helpful because it reminds me.

623
00:51:38,140 --> 00:51:40,360
 It's like, look, you want to take this affirmation thing seriously.

624
00:51:40,520 --> 00:51:42,160
 You've got to fucking do it with Heidegger, you know.

625
00:51:43,300 --> 00:51:43,620
 Yeah.

626
00:51:43,700 --> 00:51:45,820
 And I think there are good reasons for that.

627
00:51:45,920 --> 00:51:54,160
 There are good reasons to read Heidegger as not, you know, sort of committed to this notion that there is a good alternative.

628
00:51:54,320 --> 00:52:01,100
 But the writing sure as hell lends you there and as much as I've read Heidegger, I still feel that way when I read it, you know.

629
00:52:01,100 --> 00:52:09,060
 I still encounter this like, oh, yes, if we could all go live in our schwarzwalds and like make our own cabinets, you know.

630
00:52:09,060 --> 00:52:19,640
 You can see why he's really attractive for certain versions of contemporary theory because the project is at some level he wants to accommodate difference or relations,

631
00:52:19,940 --> 00:52:29,620
 which is basically the common goal of not only post-human, that kind of discourse, but most contemporary – I mean even deconstruction, right?

632
00:52:29,620 --> 00:52:38,260
 The project is accommodating or, you know, doing something with difference as opposed to reducing it or isolating categories and that sort of thing.

633
00:52:38,600 --> 00:52:43,340
 It's just that Heidegger also imbues the whole project with a sense of –

634
00:52:43,540 --> 00:52:49,540
 Yeah, nostalgia, return to something, to something that was lost and a lack of something, you know.

635
00:52:49,600 --> 00:52:50,860
 It's like – and I get that.

636
00:52:50,940 --> 00:52:54,840
 I mean everybody sort of has a vague feeling of that, right?

637
00:52:54,840 --> 00:53:02,080
 I mean with the speed of society, with information technologies, it's like we all feel a little bit like crazy, you know.

638
00:53:02,080 --> 00:53:05,660
 And it would be nice to have a return to a hardness of reality.

639
00:53:17,160 --> 00:53:31,740
 So we made the connection to Marx before and alienated labor and means of production and what's interesting to me is just how, in some ways, post-human Heidegger is in a relationship to Marx.

640
00:53:31,800 --> 00:53:48,820
 Because whereas Marx essentially cares about the laborers and alienation, Heidegger doesn't – for all of his Dasein – I mean like – well, actually, in virtue of his Dasein stuff, he doesn't talk about humans all that much.

641
00:53:48,820 --> 00:53:49,800
 He talks about –

642
00:53:49,800 --> 00:53:50,100
 No, right. No, you're right.

643
00:53:50,160 --> 00:54:15,540
 Like, I mean it is – from the – the essential term that we're always very too quick to sort of translate as man or human, you know, Dasein, you know, his concern with inauthentic relationships frankly has to do – less to do with like, you know, the exploitation of the human and more about the reduction of the would to resource.

644
00:54:15,540 --> 00:54:16,100
 Right.

645
00:54:16,200 --> 00:54:16,420
 Right.

646
00:54:16,840 --> 00:54:17,280
 Would.

647
00:54:17,380 --> 00:54:17,820
 Yeah, that's true.

648
00:54:17,840 --> 00:54:25,620
 What is being violated and it's sort of the shutting down of its capacity to relate to human involvement.

649
00:54:26,380 --> 00:54:30,580
 That's why all those object-oriented guys are all Heideggerians, you know.

650
00:54:30,740 --> 00:54:31,480
 All Heideggerians.

651
00:54:31,800 --> 00:54:38,260
 And really, I mean, they're pretty straight Heideggerians even though they want to position themselves as being sort of post-Heideggerian.

652
00:54:38,320 --> 00:54:40,300
 I feel like, you know, they're pretty straight Heideggerians.

653
00:54:40,580 --> 00:54:41,540
 But yeah.

654
00:54:41,600 --> 00:54:42,520
 But yeah, I mean it does.

655
00:54:42,800 --> 00:54:44,860
 And I think that you're absolutely right about that.

656
00:54:44,860 --> 00:54:50,760
 That sort of critique of humanism, you know, is powerful here.

657
00:54:51,060 --> 00:54:58,140
 And reconciling that with the nostalgia is – I guess it's maybe a perpetual process, right?

658
00:54:58,300 --> 00:55:03,920
 At least it is for me because I can't get past it or I have to return to it.

659
00:55:03,920 --> 00:55:11,620
 And I have to start to learn to see the nostalgia as tactical and – or as simply one mode of expression of –

660
00:55:11,620 --> 00:55:12,320
 Symptomatic.

661
00:55:12,720 --> 00:55:13,480
 Futurity, right?

662
00:55:13,620 --> 00:55:15,220
 Like it's possible to do.

663
00:55:15,380 --> 00:55:18,080
 It's just I find myself always having to do the work.

664
00:55:18,200 --> 00:55:33,840
 Like I – even though I know in the back of my head that we're going to get to a place where, oh, that craftsman who builds the cabinet isn't sort of superior or true or allowing the – I mean, when he uses the phrase like what the form of the wood wants, I just go like, oh, my fucking God.

665
00:55:33,900 --> 00:55:42,840
 Like the terms matter, the forms slumbering within it, which would be like a multiple – like it wouldn't be a form.

666
00:55:43,020 --> 00:55:51,400
 And it's not – this is not like Michelangelo who's like I see what's inside of the marble and then I take everything else away to liberate it.

667
00:55:51,480 --> 00:55:56,020
 Like a fucking piece of wood can, you know, go in a whole lot of different ways.

668
00:55:56,140 --> 00:56:01,740
 But it's harder to go in some ways than others because of the flow of the grain and the hardness and whatever else.

669
00:56:01,920 --> 00:56:02,000
 Right.

670
00:56:02,080 --> 00:56:04,620
 But I mean it gets back to the active-passive question.

671
00:56:04,720 --> 00:56:07,320
 So let's say there are 17 ways that the wood could go.

672
00:56:07,400 --> 00:56:09,660
 But what if I want to go the 18th way, right?

673
00:56:09,700 --> 00:56:16,760
 Like I mean that somehow I am being a not-true cabinetmaker if I go way 18.

674
00:56:17,100 --> 00:56:18,200
 And it's like why?

675
00:56:18,380 --> 00:56:21,560
 Why is way 18 any different than the first 17?

676
00:56:21,660 --> 00:56:26,260
 I mean when I'm out on the kayak, my kayak wants to go against the wind.

677
00:56:26,800 --> 00:56:29,320
 But I don't always want to do that, right?

678
00:56:29,320 --> 00:56:38,040
 So what my kayak wants based on, you know, aero and hydrodynamics – aerodynamics is what I was about to say.

679
00:56:39,620 --> 00:56:41,700
 That's actually a feature of your kayak.

680
00:56:43,720 --> 00:56:49,780
 You know, it's like what my kayak wants is, again, one thing, but it's just one.

681
00:56:50,000 --> 00:56:58,300
 And the idea that I am supposed to – in order to be true to the yak, I should somehow let it go where it was.

682
00:56:58,400 --> 00:57:02,940
 It's like that seems like just embracing passivity, right?

683
00:57:03,940 --> 00:57:08,860
 And giving the activity to – like, okay, the activity of objects.

684
00:57:08,960 --> 00:57:10,960
 In other words, it seems not relational at all.

685
00:57:11,580 --> 00:57:21,100
 Yeah, but the day that I see a tree pop out a chair is the day that I'll believe that the form of the chair in the wood is a passive relationship to the tree.

686
00:57:21,480 --> 00:57:22,160
 That's fine.

687
00:57:22,280 --> 00:57:23,520
 That's fair.

688
00:57:24,260 --> 00:57:24,980
 I mean I accept that.

689
00:57:24,980 --> 00:57:25,820
 Because you see the kayak.

690
00:57:26,000 --> 00:57:27,620
 The kayak is blown around, right?

691
00:57:27,660 --> 00:57:27,880
 Right.

692
00:57:27,960 --> 00:57:33,560
 But that's – there's something very different, you know, in the relationship here.

693
00:57:33,680 --> 00:57:46,360
 And to say like – look, to say that the kayaking is always a sort of like negotiating with the signs that the kayak admits in relationship to, you know, the water and wind and everything else.

694
00:57:46,360 --> 00:57:52,740
 You just have to do a lot of work on the forms slumbering within phrasing.

695
00:57:52,740 --> 00:58:09,280
 But again, I mean partly I feel like what I come up against with Heidegger is I'm frequently faced with having to do a lot of work on particular locutions in order to make them not resonate with me the way that they just instinctively do repeatedly.

696
00:58:09,820 --> 00:58:17,720
 You know, it's also like affirmation – affirmative readings don't have to preclude confrontations with the text either.

697
00:58:18,000 --> 00:58:18,620
 No, no, no, no.

698
00:58:18,620 --> 00:58:25,220
 And you shouldn't – you should never wholesale just be like this is the guy, which a lot of people do with Heidegger.

699
00:58:25,220 --> 00:58:35,300
 And it comes to the receptions and interpretations of him as the thinker of post-modernity or post-humanist scholarship, you know.

700
00:58:35,380 --> 00:58:47,720
 It's like everybody – I just feel like there's almost equal parts progressive and regressive conceptual and ethical, you know, figments within Heidegger's thinking.

701
00:58:47,720 --> 00:58:52,480
 And I don't know why you can't just sort of hold those tensions, you know.

702
00:58:52,540 --> 00:59:05,120
 It's like that almost makes him more interesting to me than just – if he were just so ruthlessly progressive and deconstructionist to the point where, you know, if there was no nostalgia in Heidegger, he wouldn't be Heidegger.

703
00:59:05,380 --> 00:59:07,560
 You know, so it's like – yeah.

704
00:59:07,940 --> 00:59:08,580
 What do you do?

705
00:59:08,680 --> 00:59:10,060
 You have to negotiate with it.

706
00:59:10,180 --> 00:59:10,460
 Right.

707
00:59:10,600 --> 00:59:14,120
 See what sorts of possibilities are slumbering within it.

708
00:59:14,260 --> 00:59:14,880
 Right, right.

709
00:59:14,940 --> 00:59:15,760
 You guys are quite right.

710
00:59:15,860 --> 00:59:17,400
 You do have to do that with everything.

711
00:59:17,520 --> 00:59:22,300
 I mean for me simply it comes down to like – I don't know.

712
00:59:22,420 --> 00:59:31,120
 The things that are – like here's what I – I'm not content with simply saying Heidegger's nostalgic and that sucks because that just is boring.

713
00:59:31,700 --> 00:59:33,300
 It's just, you know, like fine.

714
00:59:33,340 --> 00:59:34,340
 I know who Heidegger is.

715
00:59:34,340 --> 00:59:46,300
 So I'm not – you know, I'm interested in the moments that push me out of that and make me go, oh, Heidegger is something other than what I – than who I thought he was or his thinking does something other than what I thought.

716
00:59:46,500 --> 00:59:50,040
 That's the thing that does it in an interesting ways to me.

717
00:59:50,320 --> 01:00:01,120
 It's just that there are some sort of root – not – some ruts, some tracks of his one-track system that are so well-worn and so familiar.

718
01:00:01,320 --> 01:00:07,940
 I mean he's often – he's positioned often as a solution to like Cartesian thinking or humanist thinking, you know.

719
01:00:07,940 --> 01:00:17,240
 But importantly for Heidegger, again, it's – those errors of previous philosophers are in some ways necessary, right?

720
01:00:17,320 --> 01:00:18,800
 It's like – or inescapable.

721
01:00:18,980 --> 01:00:21,980
 It's kind of a Hegelian move what he does with Descartes.

722
01:00:22,120 --> 01:00:29,880
 It's like Descartes' errors when he frames the cogetto are not only a product of his circumstances but are a product of thinking.

723
01:00:29,940 --> 01:00:38,560
 It's like the withdrawal of thinking, that's what produces Descartes and it in some ways produces all of us, produces Heidegger.

724
01:00:38,900 --> 01:00:42,740
 So you don't just get to simply discard Descartes and now we're Heidegger.

725
01:00:43,120 --> 01:00:45,000
 You still have a little bit of Descartes.

726
01:00:45,140 --> 01:00:51,080
 I mean again, it's unfortunate perhaps and it has consequences to think that way but you don't just – yeah.

727
01:00:51,480 --> 01:00:55,540
 Encountering any kind of otherness means a challenge, right?

728
01:00:55,740 --> 01:00:58,600
 Like I mean interacting with you guys, no less so, right?

729
01:00:58,660 --> 01:01:02,880
 I mean we have an idiom that's familiar but we have our distinctions and it's always that.

730
01:01:03,220 --> 01:01:11,840
 And I guess to some level, you're really just sort of saying which are the challenges that sort of – that interest me the most or provoke for me the most, you know?

731
01:01:11,840 --> 01:01:20,960
 And for me at least, the nostalgic one, which I just hear a lot – I mean frankly, I hear everywhere, right?

732
01:01:20,980 --> 01:01:23,640
 Even for people that aren't Heideggerians, you know, things.

733
01:01:23,720 --> 01:01:27,540
 I'm wondering if there – how else you would treat the nostalgia?

734
01:01:27,740 --> 01:01:35,760
 Because my initial like way of dealing with it would be the kind of Zizek way where you just treat it as a symptom of a desire for truth or for – right?

735
01:01:35,840 --> 01:01:41,200
 But that to me is kind of a well-worn territory at this point too, right?

736
01:01:41,260 --> 01:01:53,440
 So like how do you manage the nostalgia without simply saying it's dumb or bad but without also just saying like it's symptomatic of a certain like humanist framework or whatever.

737
01:01:53,440 --> 01:01:53,920
 You could say this.

738
01:01:54,000 --> 01:02:04,080
 You could say it's the production of an artificial alternative that will be demonstrated to be artificial but the necessity of alternatives as you progress.

739
01:02:04,820 --> 01:02:07,180
 You know, I mean that's just – I'm just spitballing, right?

740
01:02:07,340 --> 01:02:08,680
 It's not like I've thought through this.

741
01:02:08,800 --> 01:02:09,700
 But you could say like –

742
01:02:09,700 --> 01:02:10,480
 That's a good point.

743
01:02:11,140 --> 01:02:21,640
 Just like how else are you going to be able to talk about the production of the Standing Reserve without sounding nostalgic because the relief that you're going to give it is –

744
01:02:21,640 --> 01:02:36,100
 Well, this is where I pause because you've been using the language of challenging and obviously very important in there given the specific way in which challenging matters for Heidegger's critique.

745
01:02:36,540 --> 01:02:37,240
 Challenging forth.

746
01:02:38,240 --> 01:02:38,680
 Right.

747
01:02:38,680 --> 01:02:39,060
 Right, yeah.

748
01:02:39,240 --> 01:02:47,840
 To issue forth a challenging, that configures or transforms, you know, the natural world into extractable resource.

749
01:02:48,280 --> 01:02:48,660
 That's right.

750
01:02:48,680 --> 01:03:02,780
 But, you know, if the chair is slumbering in the tree and I'm going to use some hand planes and hatchets and shit to bring it out, man, that sleeping chair got challenged.

751
01:03:03,360 --> 01:03:03,920
 Right?

752
01:03:03,920 --> 01:03:08,620
 And that's where I have –

753
01:03:08,620 --> 01:03:09,540
 Wake the fuck up, Mr. Chair.

754
01:03:10,200 --> 01:03:10,860
 I know.

755
01:03:11,840 --> 01:03:14,860
 Time to enter a new horizon, right?

756
01:03:16,280 --> 01:03:18,780
 Come out of your liminal space, Mr. Socko.

757
01:03:20,520 --> 01:03:22,220
 It's time for you to dance.

758
01:03:23,500 --> 01:03:26,960
 Yeah, talk – I mean like it's one thing to, you know, take the sock off.

759
01:03:27,160 --> 01:03:29,480
 It's the chicken with the sock on, right?

760
01:03:30,120 --> 01:03:30,480
 Yeah.

761
01:03:31,200 --> 01:03:33,500
 It's like, no, let me go back to my slumber.

762
01:03:33,920 --> 01:03:34,440
 Yeah.

763
01:03:41,200 --> 01:03:48,960
 Because I do do a decent amount of woodwork and, you know, just because of the sort of the setup of our house.

764
01:03:48,960 --> 01:03:49,300
 Oh, shit.

765
01:03:49,360 --> 01:03:50,360
 He's a Heideggerian.

766
01:03:50,500 --> 01:03:50,940
 Here we go.

767
01:03:51,380 --> 01:03:52,520
 Proper Heideggerian.

768
01:03:52,520 --> 01:03:52,820
 Wow.

769
01:03:52,840 --> 01:03:54,720
 The true relation to the planing.

770
01:03:56,100 --> 01:04:06,240
 Well, that's exactly what I want to challenge a bit is because, you know, I grew up doing woodworking mostly with power tools and I had one kind of relationship to it.

771
01:04:06,300 --> 01:04:14,840
 And because of where I live now mostly because I have to do my work predominantly in a basement that I can't stand up in that's not super well ventilated.

772
01:04:15,380 --> 01:04:21,400
 And I've shifted more to hand tools because, you know, I want to limit the amount of sawdust that I'm throwing up in the air.

773
01:04:21,500 --> 01:04:21,660
 Right, right.

774
01:04:22,680 --> 01:04:32,780
 And, you know, I've like – and what I've realized is just, one, how intertwined that is with the woodworking that I'm used to and also how different it is as well.

775
01:04:33,000 --> 01:04:37,040
 And, you know, watching various videos of, you know, people that are not purists, right?

776
01:04:37,100 --> 01:04:44,120
 They'll, like, predominantly do hand tools, but they have no problem going to use, you know, the power tool here and there.

777
01:04:44,320 --> 01:04:52,060
 And it has allowed me to relate, seriously, to the wood differently, right?

778
01:04:52,520 --> 01:05:05,440
 And, like, there is part of me that wants to say I am more authentically related to the wood as wood because I'm actually thinking of it as wood and in terms of its grain.

779
01:05:05,440 --> 01:05:16,400
 And, you know, like, I took a – I transformed a piece of firewood into a mallet, right, like, only with hand tools.

780
01:05:16,540 --> 01:05:21,580
 And not because I wanted to find a nostalgic, you know, authentic relationship to the wood.

781
01:05:21,840 --> 01:05:27,460
 It's because I didn't have a whole lot of, like, disposable money to throw into this.

782
01:05:27,560 --> 01:05:29,800
 I had a bunch of firewood that I didn't need.

783
01:05:30,300 --> 01:05:35,080
 And, you know, we were in the middle of a lockdown and I needed to just, like, bane away at something.

784
01:05:35,440 --> 01:05:45,400
 And, like, I learned shit about that wood that I never would have learned if I would have just run it through, you know, the saw.

785
01:05:45,400 --> 01:05:45,620
 I don't doubt.

786
01:05:45,620 --> 01:05:48,360
 I mean, but – I don't doubt that at all.

787
01:05:48,360 --> 01:05:50,540
 But I'm not saying that that's more authentic.

788
01:05:50,620 --> 01:05:51,240
 Yeah, it's different.

789
01:05:51,260 --> 01:05:51,420
 Right?

790
01:05:51,480 --> 01:05:53,500
 I don't want to say – yeah, it is different.

791
01:05:53,580 --> 01:05:56,780
 It produced a different relationship to the wood.

792
01:05:57,300 --> 01:06:00,540
 But that is completely unsurprising to me, right?

793
01:06:00,640 --> 01:06:06,660
 Like, that a different techno mediation is going to produce a different kind of relation.

794
01:06:07,540 --> 01:06:08,660
 And a different wood.

795
01:06:09,020 --> 01:06:09,900
 Of course it would, yeah.

796
01:06:10,020 --> 01:06:13,700
 And a different product and a different subject, right?

797
01:06:13,820 --> 01:06:16,560
 Like, I mean, there's no doubt whatsoever.

798
01:06:16,840 --> 01:06:21,480
 There's a huge, to me, huge difference between that and saying one is true and genuine.

799
01:06:21,480 --> 01:06:25,960
 And the other is standing reserve and authentic, et cetera.

800
01:06:26,140 --> 01:06:28,660
 You know, like, that to me is –

801
01:06:28,660 --> 01:06:30,440
 It's like putting on a different mask.

802
01:06:30,620 --> 01:06:34,300
 I mean, like, my relationship to handiwork is fairly minimal.

803
01:06:34,480 --> 01:06:40,620
 But when I do do it – like, I did construction for a summer and I'll occasionally put, you know, a fucking table together or something.

804
01:06:40,620 --> 01:06:51,100
 But, like, because I'm usually embroiled in academic work or, like, super technical – like, you know, doing music and it's all online and it's all with a computer.

805
01:06:51,480 --> 01:07:01,620
 When I do something that's, like, sort of real, you know, in that sense, it feels – it's satisfying because it's so different from what I usually do.

806
01:07:01,700 --> 01:07:05,820
 It's like I'm putting on the mask of a construction worker for a week or two.

807
01:07:05,880 --> 01:07:12,920
 And it's like this is a nice little game that I'm playing and it's like I get to pretend to be something that I'm usually not, you know.

808
01:07:12,960 --> 01:07:18,200
 So it's, like, it's very performative in that sense and also pretty annoying when you put it this way.

809
01:07:18,280 --> 01:07:23,480
 It's like I'm pretending to be – it's, like, it's nice to pretend to be a construction worker because I'm not a construction worker.

810
01:07:23,480 --> 01:07:26,800
 And being a construction worker all the time would probably suck.

811
01:07:27,920 --> 01:07:29,620
 But flip that around.

812
01:07:29,760 --> 01:07:47,360
 Like, someone like me who doesn't make anything and doesn't do anything, when I'm capable of doing something online, like, whether it's the editing of the things, I feel that way about the sort of, oh, man, I managed a technological feat and I am a master of the, you know, like, truthfully.

813
01:07:47,360 --> 01:08:04,800
 Like, it's – so it is – it's kind of the tinkering – the tinkering relation, it's even less about what the tools are than your relation or your familiarity or your comfort level with those kinds of – those tools or those apparatuses, you know, I suspect.

814
01:08:05,480 --> 01:08:08,640
 But what I'm doing is just sort of trying to flatten it out, right?

815
01:08:08,700 --> 01:08:20,460
 Where it's just like, look, of course, for those of us who don't do one, doing the other has a sense of satisfaction and accomplishing something has a sense of both frustration and satisfaction.

816
01:08:20,660 --> 01:08:21,140
 You know what I mean?

817
01:08:22,340 --> 01:08:50,260
 Though – so the position and intensity of something like a telos matters quite a bit in here where, you know, with the kind of hand woodworking that I was, you know, doing that, you know, the telos was really open-ended and I was able to really – you know, I was still, like, following steps and had – you know, like, I was still making a hammer.

818
01:08:50,260 --> 01:08:53,560
 Yeah, you weren't making a chair.

819
01:08:53,720 --> 01:08:55,120
 You were making a hammer, right?

820
01:08:56,060 --> 01:09:08,680
 But I was – but I also was more invested in the thing as a kind of experiment of trying to see, like, what was going to happen over the course of the production of this thing.

821
01:09:09,000 --> 01:09:30,140
 But right now I'm building an office and I'm using far fewer hand tools because I want a motherfucking functional office that I don't have until, you know, October to get it done so that I can experience, you know, the grains of every pine fiber as I'm making the thing.

822
01:09:30,460 --> 01:09:33,480
 And I get the – and I get the difference in the relationship.

823
01:09:33,680 --> 01:09:35,560
 I mean, I think this in terms of thinking sometimes.

824
01:09:36,180 --> 01:09:47,280
 So for me, I mean – and this is certainly too much information, but, like, one of the thoughts that can be deeply disturbing to me is the thought of space, like, outer space.

825
01:09:47,640 --> 01:09:58,480
 Like, I can't watch certain movies because they're in space because – and I'm aware of this, that on one level I can think about the Earth and the galaxy and it doesn't bother me.

826
01:09:58,600 --> 01:10:01,880
 Like, it's nothing – it's just like, okay, it's a little model that I picture in my head.

827
01:10:01,880 --> 01:10:12,000
 On the other hand, I can feel the sort of spatial insignificance of Earth and me and whatever, and it's absolutely panic attack – genuinely panic attack inducing.

828
01:10:12,580 --> 01:10:19,080
 And so I understand there are different relationships to thinking in those two scenarios.

829
01:10:19,300 --> 01:10:30,000
 One that treats it as, like I said, like a model of a standing reserve of an idea of a galaxy or solar system or whatever else that is completely capable of functioning with that.

830
01:10:30,000 --> 01:10:35,160
 The other is sort of feelings one's position and relationship to it, and it's terrifying.

831
01:10:35,620 --> 01:10:50,860
 And I have often, recently especially, the last few years, thought that my relationship to thinking about space and the terror that it induces in me is probably a lot like other people's relationship to thinking about, like, gay marriage.

832
01:10:51,060 --> 01:10:51,140
 Odd.

833
01:10:51,580 --> 01:10:51,960
 Right?

834
01:10:51,960 --> 01:10:58,080
 No, but I mean just like – like, that it induces this intense sense of panic.

835
01:10:58,280 --> 01:11:03,300
 And that's where this question of the relationship to thinking is, like, hugely, hugely important.

836
01:11:03,300 --> 01:11:15,280
 And the differences between ways that facilitate – I don't know, like, total panic inducing versus ways it could facilitate, like, completely functional, not a problem.

837
01:11:16,080 --> 01:11:18,020
 I have to – I mean I truly train myself.

838
01:11:18,120 --> 01:11:22,820
 It's like, like, I know when those thoughts start hitting me, often it would happen at the dog park for some reason.

839
01:11:22,900 --> 01:11:25,520
 I would just be thinking about space for some reason at the dog park.

840
01:11:25,980 --> 01:11:33,200
 But I have to train myself to think in terms of the model so that I can, like, literally, like, stand sometimes.

841
01:11:33,200 --> 01:11:46,500
 You know, and it's – to become functional requires a certain relationship of thinking, you know, which is instrumental in a way and a kind of distanced relationship.

842
01:11:47,300 --> 01:11:53,120
 So, I mean, I see value in both of those things, figuring out, like, the relative ratios.

843
01:11:53,620 --> 01:11:56,080
 And, of course, most people don't have that relationship to space.

844
01:11:56,160 --> 01:11:59,960
 They love fucking space movies, and so it's going to be different for different bodies, you know.

845
01:12:00,400 --> 01:12:02,240
 That scares the shit out of me.

846
01:12:04,680 --> 01:12:05,320
 But whatever.

847
01:12:05,640 --> 01:12:06,460
 I mean the point is not –

848
01:12:06,460 --> 01:12:09,220
 But it's literally because you need something to orient yourself.

849
01:12:09,600 --> 01:12:09,960
 Absolutely.

850
01:12:10,240 --> 01:12:10,460
 Yeah.

851
01:12:10,520 --> 01:12:11,180
 I mean –

852
01:12:11,180 --> 01:12:11,920
 Everybody does.

853
01:12:11,940 --> 01:12:14,260
 You're not a navigator, so those stars aren't doing anything for you.

854
01:12:14,260 --> 01:12:14,640
 Right.

855
01:12:14,720 --> 01:12:16,280
 I don't know how to deal with the stars.

856
01:12:16,280 --> 01:12:25,680
 But it really – I mean to me what's interesting about it is it's just – it's in some ways the same thought but a different relation to that same thought, right?

857
01:12:25,740 --> 01:12:35,440
 And I think that that's one of the things that he's after here is a thinking that's more along the lines of the panic-inducing, you know, because it's not just a thought.

858
01:12:35,600 --> 01:12:39,880
 It's not a content that one gains possession of.

859
01:12:40,000 --> 01:12:43,200
 I mean there's – you know, he's going to have much better terms for thinking of it than I do.

860
01:12:43,200 --> 01:12:45,280
 But nevertheless, like – and I get it.

861
01:12:45,360 --> 01:12:46,380
 I get the difference.

862
01:12:46,840 --> 01:12:50,620
 I get the distinction, and I get its importance to make the distinction.

863
01:12:51,060 --> 01:12:55,760
 Not all thinking of space is the same experience or the same thing or whatever.

864
01:12:56,520 --> 01:13:00,920
 But you don't have to say one's true and one's – or one's authentic and one's genuine.

865
01:13:00,920 --> 01:13:10,100
 And all of the terminology that comes along with that that leads one to be like, oh, yes, back in the good old days when we would really understand the grain of the wood.

866
01:13:13,560 --> 01:13:20,820
 It seems like what Heidegger is saying is that thinking only happens in the making molecular of the molar.

867
01:13:21,020 --> 01:13:37,420
 So you have sort of like the apparent false unity of things and thinking is always the sort of – the getting within those sets of relationships that give the false appearance of the molar and then starts to move through them.

868
01:13:37,420 --> 01:13:53,300
 But you always have to recognize that the molar itself, you know, the thing that appears to be the coherent entity that, you know, let's call it the propositional statement or let's call it Earth or let's call it the galaxy or whatever else, whatever that model is.

869
01:13:54,040 --> 01:13:57,920
 That is inauthentic.

870
01:13:57,920 --> 01:14:07,980
 And one way of thinking of this is trying to – in some ways, he's like he's missing the inventive dimension of the molar.

871
01:14:08,140 --> 01:14:08,380
 Right.

872
01:14:08,500 --> 01:14:14,980
 The problem with that is that the very distinction of the privileging of the molecular is a molar distinction, right?

873
01:14:15,060 --> 01:14:20,640
 Like that's the – in other words, what you're missing out on is the molecularizing of the molar, you know?

874
01:14:20,980 --> 01:14:26,400
 So it's – in fact, in that sense, it's the becoming molecular that's the important part, not the molecular.

875
01:14:27,220 --> 01:14:27,740
 Yeah.

876
01:14:28,200 --> 01:14:31,600
 You know, talk about the molecular would be a molarization.

877
01:14:31,760 --> 01:14:31,940
 Right.

878
01:14:32,420 --> 01:14:40,580
 But even there, or better yet, like the therapeutic capacity or the life-giving capacity of the molar.

879
01:14:40,720 --> 01:14:41,720
 I mean, as you said, like –

880
01:14:41,720 --> 01:14:43,400
 That's a better way of – I love that.

881
01:14:43,480 --> 01:14:49,240
 If we were talking about this in therapeutic terms, it would make so much more sense to me, you know?

882
01:14:50,440 --> 01:14:50,700
 Yeah.

883
01:14:50,700 --> 01:15:05,600
 I mean, it is – what it sounds like is that your relationship to – the panic-inducing relationship to space that you have is the molecularization of molar models of our position in space.

884
01:15:05,760 --> 01:15:11,480
 And as soon as you're able to molarize that outright, then like you're okay.

885
01:15:11,480 --> 01:15:12,180
 It's okay.

886
01:15:12,180 --> 01:15:13,680
 That's the grounding point.

887
01:15:13,840 --> 01:15:14,000
 Yeah.

888
01:15:14,140 --> 01:15:15,200
 It's containable.

889
01:15:15,320 --> 01:15:21,540
 But once – when everything is in play and moving, I can't fucking think – it absolutely terrifies me.

890
01:15:22,060 --> 01:15:23,660
 But you brought up like gay marriage.

891
01:15:23,820 --> 01:15:31,640
 I mean, like what is one of our favorite, you know, sort of stupid arguments to mobilize against gay marriages?

892
01:15:31,780 --> 01:15:34,340
 Usually some version of the slippery slope argument.

893
01:15:34,340 --> 01:15:34,560
 Right.

894
01:15:34,560 --> 01:15:44,140
 It's like, well, if we allow gay marriage, then we're going to allow – yeah, cats and dogs are going to, you know, have three-way marriages with humans and whatever else.

895
01:15:44,500 --> 01:15:46,220
 And like –

896
01:15:46,220 --> 01:15:47,300
 It's the same kind of logic.

897
01:15:47,300 --> 01:15:48,120
 That's what I'm saying.

898
01:15:48,220 --> 01:15:49,460
 It's the same kind of logic.

899
01:15:49,460 --> 01:15:50,440
 Everything is in motion.

900
01:15:51,200 --> 01:16:09,360
 If you destabilize the boundaries, sort of like gender expectations in relationship, so like sexual reproduction and marriage, like the boundaries that divide human from non-human are easily put into question and often do get importantly put into question.

901
01:16:09,360 --> 01:16:18,440
 But if all of that slips away at once, I mean, yeah, the, you know, the dystopia.

902
01:16:18,640 --> 01:16:19,720
 What's the – what's the vertigo?

903
01:16:20,040 --> 01:16:20,560
 The vertigo.

904
01:16:20,960 --> 01:16:21,560
 Vertigo is right.

905
01:16:21,560 --> 01:16:28,020
 And theory produces vertigo for a lot of people and it actively produces discomfort.

906
01:16:28,360 --> 01:16:35,000
 You know, when you upset those boundaries like you were just saying, I mean, that does produce a lack of orientation.

907
01:16:35,320 --> 01:16:54,100
 You know, your feet are not on the ground when you're theorizing and Heidegger seems to be interested in that, but he also kind of – like his mobilization of the poetic seems to be a way of making that vertigo again therapeutic in some way, right?

908
01:16:54,100 --> 01:17:02,080
 It's like – it's kind of an investment in the sublime where what was terrifying actually produces like ecstasy as opposed to just terror or panic, right?

909
01:17:02,100 --> 01:17:06,420
 It's interesting because I always feel like – when I think of it, I always feel like I want to live right on that edge.

910
01:17:06,560 --> 01:17:12,140
 I don't want to live in the molar comfort area and I can't live in the sort of chaotic molecular.

911
01:17:12,540 --> 01:17:19,340
 I like to live right on that edge that I can, you know, sort of be moved back and forth or move back and forth.

912
01:17:19,700 --> 01:17:24,200
 But I see – and for instance, the poetry thing is something that I've always had the same relationship to.

913
01:17:24,320 --> 01:17:28,140
 Now, I think a lot of the reason for that is because of my occupation, right?

914
01:17:28,180 --> 01:17:34,720
 Like I am in an – I'm an English professor in an English department surrounded by people who believe in the wonders of poetry.

915
01:17:34,720 --> 01:17:38,900
 And so, you know, I am just sort of instinctively cynical about that.

916
01:17:38,980 --> 01:17:43,860
 Like if I lived in a different place, I might have more of an investment in the poetic.

917
01:17:44,360 --> 01:17:51,020
 But because everyone that I'm around believes in the wonders of poetry, I'm like, oh, fucking poetry, Jesus, you know?

918
01:17:51,760 --> 01:17:51,960
 Yeah.

919
01:17:53,040 --> 01:17:53,300
 Yeah.

920
01:17:53,840 --> 01:17:55,120
 The contrarian ethos.

921
01:17:55,280 --> 01:17:56,480
 And it is that.

922
01:17:56,620 --> 01:17:58,600
 Like I – and I don't – I mean whatever.

923
01:17:58,760 --> 01:18:02,840
 It's just – I don't think that that's a good, bad, indifferent thing.

924
01:18:02,840 --> 01:18:06,840
 It's just a thing and I think it's a – you know, I mean I'm aware of it.

925
01:18:06,920 --> 01:18:07,300
 I know it.

926
01:18:07,320 --> 01:18:07,980
 But it's still there.

927
01:18:08,160 --> 01:18:14,400
 Like the fact that I recognize, you know, its history or its origins doesn't make it go away at all.

928
01:18:15,160 --> 01:18:15,420
 Right.

929
01:18:15,600 --> 01:18:21,520
 I mean the poetic is one way of relating to complexity and Heidegger likes it and that's fine.

930
01:18:21,860 --> 01:18:25,580
 But it's framing it as a panacea is odd to me.

931
01:18:25,980 --> 01:18:28,280
 You know, it's just one way of doing things.

932
01:18:28,380 --> 01:18:30,980
 You know, it's like you talk about just orientations.

933
01:18:30,980 --> 01:18:32,360
 It's just one among others.

934
01:18:32,560 --> 01:18:34,920
 It's one of the things where like I wonder about this sometimes.

935
01:18:35,140 --> 01:18:40,560
 So should philosophers do more – like for instance, a story I just told about my relationship to space.

936
01:18:40,640 --> 01:18:43,300
 If I fancy myself a philosopher, is that the kind of thing that I should talk?

937
01:18:43,360 --> 01:18:47,160
 Like look, here's a way that this body relates to questions of space.

938
01:18:47,340 --> 01:18:55,940
 And it's not – like I'm not saying the true way of relating to space is seeing – is experiencing the constant movement of celestial bodies.

939
01:18:56,300 --> 01:18:56,840
 It's not.

940
01:18:57,080 --> 01:19:00,100
 It's a – you know, it's terrifying for this body.

941
01:19:00,260 --> 01:19:08,580
 In other words, should there be even more sort of biographical or expressive disposition in –

942
01:19:08,580 --> 01:19:11,280
 There's a bit of that in Descartes' meditations.

943
01:19:11,400 --> 01:19:13,740
 Oh, Descartes' meditations is that, right?

944
01:19:14,140 --> 01:19:14,380
 Yeah.

945
01:19:15,160 --> 01:19:17,440
 Rousseau's confessions, right?

946
01:19:17,580 --> 01:19:30,220
 Like I mean there is – and I ask this very pragmatically because there have been times where I've toyed with putting that in the book here of like chunks of like almost biographical – I mean I don't simply want to do a biographical.

947
01:19:30,220 --> 01:19:38,300
 But like to have sort of biographical stuff in there of like – and it's really important that it not be simply idiosyncratic, right?

948
01:19:38,320 --> 01:19:40,280
 That it also be sort of conceptual.

949
01:19:41,140 --> 01:19:41,280
 Yeah.

950
01:19:41,700 --> 01:19:45,540
 But it's something that I've never done because I've always had such an aversion to –

951
01:19:45,540 --> 01:19:46,520
 I have trouble.

952
01:19:46,960 --> 01:19:47,520
 I have trouble.

953
01:19:47,600 --> 01:19:52,080
 Nathaniel and I talked about this I think on just the intro to the Deleuze cast.

954
01:19:52,460 --> 01:19:56,920
 I have trouble not just with biographical examples but just with examples in general.

955
01:19:57,560 --> 01:20:01,080
 Like just writing something to illustrate the theory.

956
01:20:01,760 --> 01:20:04,540
 It's like the whole – the theory is illustrating itself.

957
01:20:04,660 --> 01:20:08,440
 Why do I have to go – and it just falls apart as soon as I try to write it typically.

958
01:20:08,980 --> 01:20:12,340
 I found a couple that I can do but like it's usually a real challenge.

959
01:20:12,340 --> 01:20:17,080
 But illustrate is actually a good word there in the sense that it's not reflecting the theory.

960
01:20:17,500 --> 01:20:18,500
 It is filling it out.

961
01:20:18,600 --> 01:20:19,820
 Like it's doing something.

962
01:20:20,300 --> 01:20:23,740
 Because to me when I took the space example, I remember thinking right before I said that.

963
01:20:23,820 --> 01:20:26,640
 I was like this is going to take us in a slightly different direction.

964
01:20:27,820 --> 01:20:29,960
 It's jumping off from the point that we're talking about.

965
01:20:30,040 --> 01:20:33,440
 So it's not an example in the sense of the general particular.

966
01:20:33,860 --> 01:20:40,240
 It is just a concrete instantiation from the theoretical point that will go somewhere else, right?

967
01:20:40,240 --> 01:20:41,820
 It will be – it's not unrelated.

968
01:20:42,940 --> 01:20:50,140
 That's what's so hard about coming up with examples is despite the fact that I think all three of us would very quickly sort of like dismiss the –

969
01:20:50,140 --> 01:20:57,340
 the very possibility of an example, quote example, still kind of feel that need.

970
01:20:57,480 --> 01:21:11,880
 They're like, all right, I need to – you know, I need to embody the thing that I've just said rather than find something else that has a particular kind of alliance with it that will, you know, do some explanatory kind of work in taking to it.

971
01:21:11,880 --> 01:21:14,820
 But it's also going to launch me in a different direction.

972
01:21:15,000 --> 01:21:15,200
 Right.

973
01:21:16,200 --> 01:21:29,280
 I found – because usually, at least pedagogically, examples are meant to clarify or to make – to reify almost, you know, make something a little bit more graspable by the students.

974
01:21:29,280 --> 01:21:35,460
 But in writing, I find that it's just so – I want the example to just do something weird.

975
01:21:35,800 --> 01:21:42,820
 Like, you know, just like – just like not even – not explain anything really or just make it even less comprehensible.

976
01:21:43,040 --> 01:21:43,920
 So do that.

977
01:21:44,300 --> 01:21:51,480
 Like that's – I mean that's exactly – in other words, there's a logic to exemplarity that's really important for the kind of work that we do.

978
01:21:51,480 --> 01:21:58,900
 Because there is a demand both from within us and from external sources of like give us something concrete, right?

979
01:21:59,020 --> 01:22:00,520
 That is a demand.

980
01:22:01,160 --> 01:22:05,380
 And like, hey, okay, I'll give you something concrete and it's not going to clarify anything.

981
01:22:21,480 --> 01:22:29,320
 And like, hey, I'll give you something concrete and it's not going to clarify anything.

